\par\par \b \uc2 11TH ASEAN SUMMIT MUST BE REALISTIC IN CHOOSING COOPERATION PROGRAMS  \b0\par\par\uc2 1,711 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 December 2005\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 Asia Pulse Pty Limited. Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its negligence or otherwise.  \par \par \uc2 By L. Panca Hari Prabowo  \par \par \uc2 Jakarta, Dec 5 (ANTARA) - The 11th Summit of the Association of South-East Asian Nations (ASEAN) is scheduled to take place in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, from December 12 to 14, 2005.  \par \par \uc2 A number of questions arise about the direction of ASEAN development and the implementation of a number of agreements already declared.  \par \par \uc2 According to Dr. Yasmin Sungkar, senior researcher of the Center for Political Studies (P2P) in the Indonesian Institute of Sciences (LIPI), ASEAN with so many programs must be more realistic in selecting cooperation programs to ensure that the programs will not only rest in agreements.  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia cannot hope much from ASEAN, especially in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  aspect, as the realization of intra-SEAN \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  cooperation is slow, whereas Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems needs immediate solution.  \par \par \uc2 ASEAN establishment was declared in Bangkok, Thailand, on August 8, 1967 by five founders, namely Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore and Thailand. Brunei Darussalam joined the group on January 7, 1984, followed consecutively by Vietnam, Laos, Myanmar and Cambodia from 1995 to 1999.  \par \par \uc2 Timor Leste serves as an observer in the regional association. The ten ASEAN member countries, according to data presented by Wikipedia website, have a total territory of 4.5 million sq.km. and a total population of about 500 million.  \par \par \uc2 ANTARA's interview with Dr. Yasmin Sungkar via e-mail on 11th ASEAN Summit, in connection with ASEAN cooperation with the European Union, cooperation in fighting terrorism and avian influenza and tripartite cooperation among ASEAN members, is as follows:  \par \par \uc2 ANTARA (ANT): What can we expect from the 11th ASEAN Summit, especially concerning the agreements linked with Indonesia's interests, especially in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  field and general aspect in bringing the ASEAN vision into reality?  \par \par \uc2 Yasmin Sungkar (YS): Many agreements have been signed in ASEAN summits. However, it is necessary to find out whether the piling up of agreements have been or can be converted into reality. So far many old agreements have been left untouched with the emergence of new agreements.  \par \par \uc2 For the fulfillment of national interests, especially in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  field, Indonesia cannot hope much from ASEAN. The realization of ASEAN \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  cooperation is slow, whereas \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems troubling Indonesia need immediate settlement.  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia can struggle at regional or international levels to meet its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  interests, but such efforts need long-term negotiations. The more important thing for that purpose is preventing the collision between regional agreements and national interests.  \par \par \uc2 ANT: Is the ASEAN forum beneficial to all member countries or only part of its members?  \par \par \uc2 YS: Essentially ASEAN has been established to accommodate common interests in Southeast Asia. The ASEAN forum, which covers various issues, always accommodates the interests of all member countries. On the one hand, ASEAN members want to step together, but on the other hand their condition varies in the political as well as \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  levels. For that reason, there are countries that feel unfavorable by the presence of ASEAN. But actually the ASEAN forum is beneficial to all of its members.  \par \par \uc2 Besides a meeting of ASEAN leaders, several meetings between ASEAN and dialogue partner countries are also held in an ASEAN Summit. In the 11th ASEAN Summit, for instance, ASEAN leaders are scheduled to hold their 11th meetings with their dialogue partners from China, Japan, and South Korea, and other meetings. In the 11th Summit in Kuala Lumpur, ASEAN will hold its first dialogue with Russia, formerly part of the disbanded Soviet Union.  \par \par \uc2 The first East Asia Summit scheduled for December 14, 2005 is another important event to be held this year. According to the 11th ASEAN Summit website, this summit is aimed at strengthening the position of ASEAN in dealing with regional and international issues effectively in productive ways.  \par \par \uc2 ANT: It seems that ASEAN makes the European Union as a standard of comparison or a model for the future form of ASEAN, as reflected in ASEAN cooperation, for instance, cooperation in the construction and operation of a fertilizer plant and other kinds of cooperation that have also been practiced by some EU member countries at the beginning of the EU establishment.  \par \par \uc2 Is it possible for ASEAN, with a collision of interests among its members, to follow the European Union? The EU leads to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social integration though its members still maintain their respective sovereignty.  \par \par \uc2 YS: ASEAN and the European Union are very much different in the form of organization. ASEAN is a quite loose regional organization that still adheres to the consensus principle to accommodate the interests of its members, while the EU is a solider regional organization with higher integration.  \par \par \uc2 For example, ASEAN has faced difficulty to accommodate the common interests of its members in the joint effort to build a fertilizer plant, so that it is difficult to maintain the operation of the plant.  \par \par \uc2 This failure should become a lesson to ASEAN so that this regional organization will be more realistic in choosing cooperation programs.  \par \par \uc2 The desire to enhance ASEAN integration is frequently bruited about, but ASEAN evolution is still far from the form of the European Union as a regional organization. ASEAN should manage to narrow the gap between its members first before stepping further to deeper \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social integration.  \par \par \uc2 ANT: If it is impossible for ASEAN to follow the European Union model, what are the reasons causing the inability?  \par \par \uc2 YS: Since the beginning ASEAN has been expected to become a binding regional cooperation group, and now ASEAN wants to enhance its integration, while at the same time still sticks to the principles it has followed so far.  \par \par \uc2 Flexibility, patience, evolution and consensus characterize ASEAN, but such characteristic is contrary to the type of a binding organization like the European Union. Therefore, it is difficult for ASEAN to become a solid regional grouping like the European Union with an authorized commission, which can implement the decisions of EU members. Or perhaps ASEAN does not want to become a binding organization.  \par \par \uc2 ANT: Indonesia will propose the avian influenza and terrorism issues as one of the topics to be discussed in the ASEAN Summit. What Indonesia can expect from that proposed topic?  \par \par \uc2 YS: Indonesia has chosen an appropriate topic on avian flu and terrorism as the two issues have threatened national, regional and international communities. Concerted efforts are required to eradicate avian flu as a border crossing threat and terrorism as a transnational crime.  \par \par \uc2 The ASEAN Summit is expected to decide collective actions to get ride of avian flu. Besides providing various kinds of transparent information, the summit is expected to turn out joint action programs that can be implemented immediately by each ASEAN country.  \par \par \uc2 ANT: Has ASEAN countries developed strong cooperation in fighting terrorism or fought this crime only for the sake of superpower's interest in the country stricken by terrorist actions?  \par \par \uc2 YS: Terrorist actions have broken out everywhere, threatening not only the superpower. Therefore, ASEAN members have agreed to intensify cooperation in fighting terrorism. So far countries stricken by terrorist attacks have shown strong cooperation with the superpower due to the availability of facilities and funds in that strong country. The eradication of terrorism needs facilities, trained personnel and people's participation.  \par \par \uc2 Besides serving as the host of the 11th ASEAN Summit, Malaysia will also host other important meetings, namely the second Meeting of the Eastern ASEAN Growth Area (EAGA) involving Brunei Darussalam, Indonesia, Malaysia and the Philippines, and the first Meeting of the Indonesia-Malaysia-Thailand Growth Triangle. Four other ASEAN members, namely Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar and Vietnam will also hold their second cooperation meeting in Kuala Lumpur.  \par \par \uc2 Intra-ASEAN cooperation and cooperation between ASEAN and its dialogue partners have formed so many forums. The presence of those forums arises a question whether they will contribute to the ASEAN progress.  \par \par \uc2 ANT: The ASEAN Mutual Legal Assistance Agreement, the ASEAN Convention on Counter Terrorism, the ASEAN Extradition Treaty, as well as the ASEAN Defense Ministers Meeting and ASEAN Maritime Forum have begun to work. Will those forums be effective to support the progress of ASEAN and its members?  \par \par \uc2 YS: The formation of those forums and cooperation agreements is important and beneficial to ASEAN as a regional organization. However, their contribution to the progress of ASEAN countries is still \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . It is clear that those forums are not disadvantageous to ASEAN, but have a different beneficial effect on each ASEAN member, depending on the priority and interest of the country.  \par \par \uc2 ANT: How is the ideal organizational form and cooperation pattern for ASEAN in the future, especially in connection with the forthcoming 40th anniversary of this organization of the Southeast Asian countries.  \par \par \uc2 YS: With the age of approaching 40, ASEAN as an organization is relatively no longer young. There are goals that have been and that have yet to be met. ASEAN development is not free from the impact of external changes.  \par \par \uc2 It is not easy, therefore, to cite the ideal organizational form for ASEAN in the future. This form of this regional organization has continued to develop, from ASEAN-5 to ASEAN-6 and the ASEAN-10, and now ASEAN + 3. East Asia Summit is scheduled to be held shortly, though value added derived from the expansion of the forum is still \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Such developments indicate that ASEAN is not stagnant and still open to cooperation with countries outside ASEAN, in accordance with the new demand of the region.  \par \par \uc2 It is clear that ASEAN must be realistic in selecting cooperation programs to ensure that the programs will not only rest in agreements. ASEAN's efforts to improve the welfare of the Southeast Asian region must involve the non-\b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector and the community.  \par \par \uc2 The 11th ASEAN Summit with theme "One Vision, One Identity, One Community" is expected to become a means of communications between the leaders of ASEAN member countries in making evaluation and studying the implementation of ASEAN cooperation agreements and in exploring the possibility making new cooperation agreements in several other fields.  \par \par \uc2 The 11th ASEAN Summit is also expected to strengthen ASEAN relations with its dialogue partners, namely China, Japan, South Korea, India and Russia. The first East Asia Summit to be held shortly is intended to foster ASEAN countries' closer relations with China, Japan, South Korea, India, Australia and New Zealand.  \par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020051206e1c50000n\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
