\par\par \b \uc2 Maintain momentum to overcome challenges  \b0\par\par\uc2 Stephen Schwartz , Jakarta  \par \uc2 1,255 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 December 2005\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 18\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Judging by the stock and foreign exchange markets over the past few weeks, the coming of the New Year and a recent cabinet reshuffle have brought fresh hope to Indonesian market-watchers that macroeconomic stability will endure, and that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth will continue to rise toward its enormous potential. However, while prospects are bright, especially over the medium term, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  at present is showing signs of a slowdown and inflation is high. Consequently, projections for 2006 are subject to more than the usual range of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and important challenges confront the new \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team and \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the year ahead.  \par \par \uc2 While GDP growth has been picking up in recent years, to over 5 percent in 2004 and most likely in 2005 as well, the government recognizes that an even stronger pickup to at least the 6 percent range will be needed over the medium term if Indonesia's high unemployment and poverty rates are to be addressed effectively. To achieve this goal and to counter the current slowdown, the new \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team will need to accelerate regulatory, institutional, and other reforms to improve the investment climate.  \par \par \uc2 But before turning to the challenges confronting policymakers, it is useful to remind ourselves just how far Indonesia has come since the Asian financial crisis of 1997-1998, and to reflect on developments over the past year. When the financial crisis engulfed much of Asia, Indonesia was the hardest hit, with real GDP falling by 13 percent in 1998, the rupiah undergoing a massive depreciation, and inflation soaring to more than 70 percent.  \par \par \uc2 With the implementation of sound policies since those turbulent times, per capita GDP has risen to well above pre-crisis levels, the banking system -- while in need of further strengthening, particularly in parts of the state bank sector -- has been restored to reasonable health, and the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  debt-to-GDP ratio is on a sustainable and declining path. All of this has occurred even as Indonesia underwent a historic political transition, culminating in last year's peaceful direct Presidential election.  \par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, the government has had to manage a number of shocks to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the past year, including the aftermath of the tragic tsunami, the second Bali bombing, and the steep rise in international oil prices and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  (and most recently, the threat of Avian Flu). Macroeconomic stability, which had increasingly (and perhaps prematurely) been taken as given, came under strain, particularly last August and September when the rupiah depreciated sharply and foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  declined.  \par \par \uc2 The situation stabilized quickly once \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) raised \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in a convincing manner -- thereby catching up with global interest rate developments over the previous months -- and the government announced its bold decision to reign in fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  through an adjustment in domestic fuel prices. The previous \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team and BI deserve credit for navigating the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  through the many shocks, and for implementing \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  adjustments convincingly, if somewhat belatedly. The episode serves as a reminder that preserving macroeconomic stability is a day-to-day challenge, and of the importance of taking early \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  action when needed in response to a changing international \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  environment.  \par \par \uc2 As the calendar year comes to a close, financial market confidence remains reasonably strong and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is on a sound footing. Nevertheless, as noted above, the near-term \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook for 2006 is subject to \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Inflation accelerated sharply following the October fuel price increase, and currently stands above 18 percent (year-on-year). \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  has, appropriately, raised \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  further to contain inflationary pressures. While the rise in inflation is largely due to the impact of the fuel price increase, underlying (or "core") inflation, which excludes food, energy, and administrative price changes, had been picking up since late 2004 and is still high.  \par \par \uc2 Inevitably, the impact of the rise in \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , October's fuel price increase, and the associated erosion of consumer purchasing power are likely to result in some slowing of growth during the final quarter of 2005 and first half of 2006. Signs of a slowdown are already evident in data on retail sales and surveys of consumer and business confidence, although admittedly the picture is mixed, with some indicators such as motorcycle sales holding up, and some businesses still reporting robust sales.  \par \par \uc2 The good news is that, with a continued supportive global environment (which is, however, subject to risks) and with sound policies, prospects are good for a pickup in private consumption and investment later in the year. As such, IMF staff believe that for the year as a whole growth in the 5 percent range is feasible for 2006.  \par \par \uc2 Moreover, if BI is successful in containing inflationary expectations, an important determinant in wage and price setting, inflation by end year could well decline to the 8 percent range, in line with BI's latest projections. (Measured on a year-on-year basis, inflation is expected to remain in the 16-18 percent range for some time due to the base effect of the fuel price increase, although the month-to-month inflation rates should moderate.)  \par \par \uc2 But achieving even a 5 percent level of growth in 2006 will require determined efforts by \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  makers in the areas of both macroeconomic management and structural reforms. On the macroeconomic front, as mentioned above, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  faces the challenge of raising its interest rate to contain inflation, in the context of the recently adopted inflation targeting framework, without unduly weakening consumption and investment growth.  \par \par \uc2 At the same time, with overall \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2005 running below budgeted levels, the government will need to ensure that administrative bottlenecks are removed so that \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  -- including some carryover of unspent funds in 2005 that would still leave the overall \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  within a prudent level -- is executed in a timely way. In so doing, the government should focus on high priority areas, including education, health, and infrastructure projects.  \par \par \uc2 The previous \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team rightly emphasized reforms to enhance the investment climate as key to stimulating growth. With private investment growth now showing some signs of weakening, the challenge for the new \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team will be to reinvigorate the reform process, whose implementation momentum appears to have slowed in recent months.  \par \par \uc2 The list of needed reforms is well known: They include efforts to improve \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  administration, both to enhance revenue collection and provide fairness to taxpayers; a more flexible labor market; upgrades to Indonesia's lagging infrastructure; and strengthening legal certainty and governance.  \par \par \uc2 The government has been making progress in all of these areas, but will need to ensure that the momentum is maintained, for example, by resolving differences over the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  laws now in Parliament. In addition, continued efforts to strengthen the financial sector, including sound banking supervision and improvements in the asset quality of state-owned banks, would help reduce vulnerabilities and enhance the ability of the banking sector to support private \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity. To implement this agenda effectively, coordination and prioritization will be critical.  \par \par \uc2 The market's favorable response to the installation of the new \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team is an indication that hopes are high. But the challenges before the new team are difficult, and it would be unfair to expect one or two Ministers alone to be able to turn around a slowing \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . To succeed, the new team will need to maintain an unfailing commitment to the reform process, with the full support of their fellow Ministers, Parliamentarians, and the international community.  \par \par \uc2 The writer is Senior Resident Representative, IMF Jakarta Office.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020051231e1cv00017\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\pic