\par\par \b \uc2 Was 2005 a year of missed opportunities? Yes, says IPA chief   \b0\par\par\uc2 The year that just ended saw global oil prices soar by about 40 percent during the course of the year. Yet, as its oil output continued to decline, Indonesia missed out on a potentially larger piece of the world's oil revenue. The president of the Indonesian Petroleum Association,   Chris Newton ,  shared his thoughts on how 2005 treated the domestic oil and gas sector with  The Jakarta Post's  Leony Aurora .  The following is an excerpt of the interview:   \par \uc2 957 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 January 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Question: How do you see 2005 for the oil and gas sector? Answer: The year 2005 was viewed at the beginning as a defining year, against a background of falling production, the near loss of net oil exporter status, falling exploration investment and a new government that recognizes the strategic importance of the industry and the requirement to increase investment.   \par \par \uc2 Now, in reflection, I see an industry that is still struggling to realize anywhere near its full potential. Production of oil and gas has continued to decline and output is only marginally ahead of consumption. We have had a very strong oil price environment, which flowed into companies' profits and cash flows. However, investment in exploration, the future of the industry, is still stagnating at near 35-year lows.   \par \par \uc2 Existing and prospective investors were independently surveyed by PricewaterhouseCoopers during the year. Regulatory and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  consistency, legal certainty and bureaucratic inefficiency were unequivocally identified as key issues reducing Indonesia's competitiveness -- not geological prospectivity.   \par \par \uc2 Was 2005 a year of missed opportunities? Yes -- pretty much. (However), the IPA board is optimistic that with some quick and decisive actions, the industry can be turned around.   \par \par \uc2 What were the main achievements in 2005? I think we should recognize and applaud the regulatory progress that has been made.   \par \par \uc2 The President has shown a clear vision, which is to increase oil production to 1.3 million barrels per day by 2009.   \par \par \uc2 The government has also taken decisive action on petroleum product \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  that were fiscally unsustainable and distorting the rational allocation of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  resources. A total of 15 contracts were signed, including seven new production sharing contracts (PSCs). Unfortunately, the international oil and gas firms, with their skills, technology and risk capital that are very much needed for frontier exploration that could turn the industry around, have largely been absent.   \par \par \uc2 The world is looking at the resolution of the Cepu dispute as a litmus test of the government's ability to stimulate investment in a project of immense national interest. There has been some progress on Cepu with the signing of a new cooperation contract. It is disappointing, however, that it was not resolved by year's end, let alone during the new government's first 100 days.   \par \par \uc2 On the regulatory side, a number of decrees aimed at resolving investors' nightmares on value-added \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  reimbursement, customs duty and \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  on imports have been signed. Some US$210 million of un-reimbursed VAT for 2004 and part of 2005 was finally paid, although as of today I believe we are up to some $130 million outstanding again.   \par \par \uc2 This is not helping investor confidence, nor is the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  office's refusal to honor binding Supreme Court decisions in 2000 on deferred VAT, in which the industry is owed another $100 million.   \par \par \uc2 Another promising development is the first-ever service station by a foreign investor opened in Jakarta, as enabled by the new oil and gas law, with a lot more to come.   \par \par \uc2 What issues remain and what are the obstacles to resolving them? Lack of \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  certainty, clarity and consistency is probably the biggest factor detracting from Indonesia's investment competitiveness.   \par \par \uc2 There is a minefield of inconsistencies between the oil and gas law, proposed new \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  laws, PSCs and regulations.   \par \par \uc2 For example, the 2005 PSC was introduced with the elimination of \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on exploration investment, calling for the government to assume and discharge the VAT, customs duties and other \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on imports. Although this was a big step forward, this incentive is inconsistent with Law No. 22/2001 (on oil and gas) and hence its effectiveness is \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 The late 2004 Constitutional Court annulments of sections of Law No. 22 have still not been resubmitted to the legislature. I am not sure what the obstacles are for this, as the IPA's input was (already) completed back in the first half of the year.   \par \par \uc2 The first draft of the new \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  laws leaves many critical oil and gas issues unaddressed. However, the delay in the introduction of the package of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform laws provides an opportunity to get things right and restore industry competitiveness. The IPA is advocating for refinements of laws and regulations with three clear principles, namely certainty and consistency of the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  regime, continued retention of the uniformity principle and the encouragement of exploration investment.   \par \par \uc2 What homework does the government have for next year? In a depletion business, not investing is not an option, and every day other countries are finding new ways to attract investment. The reality is that Indonesia's share of global upstream capital allocation has declined from 8 percent to 3 percent over the past five years, indicating eroded competitiveness.   \par \par \uc2 Item one on the agenda toward improved competitiveness has to be harmonizing regulations with each other and existing PSCs. Item two has to be to maintain the regulatory reform momentum and resolve outstanding issues, including VAT reimbursement, oil and gas law resubmission to the legislature and contract sanctity issues such as gas DMO.   \par \par \uc2 Item three is defiantly developing a new and more efficient partnership between regulators and investors that delivers on regulatory objectives, while at the same time delivering on investors' objectives of investing quickly and efficiently.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060102e2120000z\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
