ion of industries from Indonesia to other countries, Kalla said he was not worried about it because what had been relocated were possibly mere footloose industries such as shoes and textile industries.   \par \par \uc2 Asked if there was a guarantee that Japanese investors would increase their investment in Indonesia, he said investors would come by themselves if they saw a good business climate as they would always seek safe and efficient places for their investment.   \par \par \uc2 "What is important for us is creating a good business climate so that they are willing to come and those who have been here will not go," he said.   \par \par \uc2 On Indonesia's preparations ahead of the signing of the EPA draft, Kalla said that the government had already submitted a draft law on manpower to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  and it was expected to be finished in six months. He said the government would also immediately submit a draft law on capital investment to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  for approval.   \par \par \uc2 While in Japan, Kalla paid a courtesy call on Prime Minister Junichiro Koizumi and met with a number of big company executives such as from Hitochu, Toyo Menka, Marubeni and Mitsui. He had also met with the ruling party leaders and attended a seminar on investment in Indonesia held by the Japanese Insitute of International Affairs and the Japanese Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Keidanren).   \par \par \uc2 On various occasions in Japan, Kalla emphasized the importance of mutually-beneficial partnership and asked for easier requirements for loans fron that country.   \par \par \uc2 Japan meanwhile had expressed fear that Indonesia might stop LNG supply to that country following the government's new \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to prioritize domestic need.   \par \par \uc2 Kalla however said that Indonesia would respect the commitment it had made and would not break contracts for LNG supply that had been signed.   \par \par \uc2 "After the contracts have expired we will prioritize domestic need. That is another question," he said.   \par \par \uc2 Kalla meanwhile focussed on assuring all parties on what Indonesia had done and would do to improve the business and investment climate while in Belgium and Finland.   \par \par \uc2 Businessmen in the two countries generally were worried about security situation, legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and corrupt practices in Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020060127e21q00011\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
