\par\par \b \uc2 Business-solution center   \b0\par\par\uc2 709 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 February 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Industry Minister Fahmi Idris's remarks last week that essentially blamed businesspeople largely for the high costs of doing business is further evidence of how ignorant many senior government officials still are of the inordinately high bureaucratic and regulatory costs in the country.   \par \par \uc2 The outright rejection by the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin) of the government's plan to increase electricity rates without waiting for the investigative audit of the structure of the production costs of the electricity monopoly, (PT PLN), is rather unreasonable. Kadin argued that businesses could no longer bear additional costs from higher electricity rates as they are already suffering great burdens caused by the steep fuel price hikes last October and their multiplier impact.   \par \par \uc2 However, simply blaming the business community for the high production costs in the country shows either a complete ignorance or self-denial on the part of senior government officials of the gross inefficiency and high degree of venality within the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector.   \par \par \uc2 But we don't believe that officials are not aware of the bureaucratic and regulatory problems facing the business sector. They are instead more in self-denial because many officials also benefit from the currently inefficient, corrupt system.   \par \par \uc2 Various national and international surveys, for example, have concluded that the inordinately high costs of doing business are the main barrier to investment, notably those from overseas. And quite a portion of the costs has been derived from inefficiency and corruption in the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector.   \par \par \uc2 A study of large export-oriented industrial companies at four of Indonesia's largest seaports last year concluded that logistics services account for an average 14 percent of total production costs and the high logistics costs were derived mainly from poor infrastructure, illegal levies and arduous bureaucratic procedures.   \par \par \uc2 Low costs of logistics and superior logistics management -- low transportation costs, short transit times, reliable delivery schedules, careful handling of goods in cold storage chains -- are vital for trade and smooth distribution of goods.   \par \par \uc2 The latest survey by the International Finance Corporation released late last year, the World Bank's arm for private sector development, ranks Indonesia 113th out of 155 countries surveyed for its Doing Business in 2006: Creating Jobs report, which measures the competitiveness of a country as a place for doing business.   \par \par \uc2 Fahmi's controversial remarks make it even more imperative now for chief economics minister Boediono to strengthen coordination of all economics ministers in a special task force or a business-solution center where officials and businesspeople could frankly discuss and resolve any problems encountered in the manufacturing and trade sectors.   \par \par \uc2 The need for better coordination becomes increasingly urgent, especially after the split of the trade and industry ministry in 2004 into two separate entities.   \par \par \uc2 The major problems that affect industry and trade such as inefficient and corrupt \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and customs service, port handling, poor transportation infrastructure, lack of credit financing, radical trade unions and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about law enforcement are completely outside the two ministries' authority.   \par \par \uc2 The inter-ministerial forum could function as a crisis-management center or a war-room like operation center where the political and bureaucratic leadership regularly meet face to face with representatives of the business community to discuss and resolve problems with most urgency.   \par \par \uc2 Any issues related to the business or investment operations could be settled quickly at the highest level of the executive branch. The basic idea of such a mechanism is that even though the political and macroeconomic stability has been strengthening, the magnitude of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems we are now encountering is such that our condition is still critical.   \par \par \uc2 Since job-seekers throughout the country are now estimated at around 11 million and are increasing daily as not a single day passes without one or two companies making worker layoffs and the number of under-employed remains large at more than 30 million our condition is nothing else but critical.   \par \par \uc2 An \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis should be managed as the emergency room of a hospital where fast decisions and concrete programs of action are much more important than bureaucratic procedures or rigidities.   \par \par \uc2 The government should fully realize that it is investment, not the government, that creates jobs and nobody makes new investment if the costs of doing business remain much higher than other countries.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060214e22e0000n\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
