\par\par \b \uc2 Natural resources sector needs govt attention   \b0\par\par\uc2 Rendi Akhmad Witular , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 1,394 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 March 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 With the country's manufacturing sector still in the doldrums, mostly due to high costs and labor problems, the potential of the natural resources sector has yet to be fully tapped by the government.   \par \par \uc2 As one of the world's main exporters of several commodities, including liquefied natural gas (LNG), coal, crude palm oil, tin and pulp, there has been little effort by the government to encourage more investors into the sector.   \par \par \uc2 Giant U.S. securities house Merrill Lynch sees the main advantage possessed by Indonesia compared to other emerging economies, such as China and India, as its abundant supplies of natural resources rather than its manufacturing capabilities.   \par \par \uc2 Even the government's recently introduced \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform package has not paid sufficient attention to the natural resources sector, raising doubts as to whether the country will be able to make optimum use of its resources to generate higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.   \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post recently interviewed Merrill Lynch's Indonesian office president, Roger Suyama, who is also head of investment banking for Indonesia, and sought his views on the current investment situation in Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 Merrill Lynch, which only has two main offices in Southeast Asia -- Jakarta and Singapore -- has positioned Indonesia as one of its main focuses in terms of franchising, deals and profitability.   \par \par \uc2 The company, which last year managed underwriting and advisory businesses worth more than US$1 billion, is currently increasing its capacity to anticipate rapid progress in the country's natural resources sector.   \par \par \uc2 The following are excerpts from the interview with the U.S.-born Suyama:   \par \par \uc2 How do you see the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in general now?   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team and the administration are very positive for investors. International investors are quite confident about what the administration has been doing. Look at what they have done in resolving the fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  issue and the Cepu (oil block) problem.   \par \par \uc2 They are taking steps to get international investor confidence by, among other things, cracking down on corruption. All these things are viewed by investors as positive.   \par \par \uc2 For the Cepu imbroglio, for example, although the settlement has not been quick, it looks like it is getting closer to being resolved. It takes a lot of time, but in a democratic country -- especially in a new democracy -- sometimes taking hard decisions takes a lot of time to do. But investors overall are very positive. What about the sectors that investors favor now?   \par \par \uc2 Investors are mostly interested in natural resources sectors, such as oil and gas, coal, crude palm oil and pulp. So, natural resources exports are the most attractive. Investors will choose these before looking at the consumer and retail sectors.   \par \par \uc2 Regardless of what happens in Indonesia, natural resources will continue to be in high demand worldwide. The growth of China and India, as well as Indonesia, means more resources are going to be used up by these countries in all areas.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's comparative advantage over China and India is in the natural resources sector. Indonesia is the second largest exporter of coal, largest exporter of LNG, and has still unexploited oil and gas \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 . There are also huge stretches of land and plantation products that could be further developed. The country is expected to continue exporting these natural resources. What about in manufacturing sector?   \par \par \uc2 There isn't much international interest in the manufacturing sector. But it depends on the type of manufacturing. The automobile industry, for example, is quite interesting for many investors as it holds out the prospect of huge domestic sales.   \par \par \uc2 There is more competition (for Indonesia) in the manufacturing sector. Both China and India have very competitive manufacturing sectors where the profit margins are higher than in Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia is more competitive in developing the natural resources sector. It is not that international investors are not interested in the country's manufacturing sector, it is just that they think the natural resources sector is more profitable. Do you think the government should focus more on this sector in the short term?   \par \par \uc2 That seems to be what the market is saying. There is plenty of money worldwide for Indonesia to develop its natural resources sector, whether it be fisheries, paper and pulp, palm oil or mining. So there is a lot of interest. In terms of \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , what investors look for is consistency. So, whatever the laws are, they should be applied consistently to both domestic and international investors.   \par \par \uc2 The more consistent the government is in applying the law, the more confidence investors will have in investing in Indonesia. So, the biggest problem for investors is \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . How do you see the recent capital inflows into Indonesia? Do they result from hot money or from rising confidence in the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals?   \par \par \uc2 Well, I think it is a combination of people who believe in the fundamentals in Indonesia and its natural resources sector, and those who believe in making short-term investments. But obviously, when a country does very well you have both fundamental money and more short-term money.   \par \par \uc2 But you see this everywhere, including in Japan. The investment horizon of investors worldwide tends to be short, so there is probably more hot money going around but it is very difficult to predict where this money will go next.   \par \par \uc2 The Philippines and Thailand are politically unfavorable right now for certain investors. Therefore, some of that (short-term) investment is being allocated to Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 However, there is also new money that is going to emerging markets like Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 The major capital flows generally come from the United States and Europe, and other parts of Asia. But for the last year and a half, we have seen more interest from U.S investors. Three years ago, their interest was fairly low, but now we are seeing much higher interest from them. What makes U.S. investors more confident given current security threats?   \par \par \uc2 I think investors see the terrorist threat as being everywhere. This threat is something investors have to live with. Indonesia has led the fight against terrorism and that is good.   \par \par \uc2 Another factor is the election of the new administration. I think people are very positive about what this administration is doing. There is also progress in relations between Indonesia and the United States. There is a feeling in the United States and Europe that this government is making a very definite effort to resolve issues that are of concern to investors.   \par \par \uc2 Besides that, the cash flow of Indonesian companies today compared to five or even three years ago is much higher and better. The difference today compared to 1996 and 1997 is that there is less debt, and the type of the debt now is more longer term.   \par \par \uc2 The banking sector is also healthier, and you see more natural resources company with higher profitability compared to back in 1996. What about compared to other Southeast Asian countries? Are investment conditions here still competitive?   \par \par \uc2 It is always difficult to make a comparison. Indonesia, relative to some other countries, seems to have made quite good progress. The Philippines and Thailand have seen some political turmoil and concerns.   \par \par \uc2 When compared to these two countries, Indonesia seems to be consistently growing and is perceived to have very good \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies. Now, Indonesia is being compared to China and India. But the government needs to do more to make that comparison relevant.   \par \par \uc2 I think the government should continue fighting corruption, resolving pending issues, creating a more conducive investment environment and maintaining consistent policies. And also, there is a need to encourage investors to come here to develop the natural resources sector.   \par \par \uc2 I also think that it is important for Indonesia to be inclusive by allowing all business groups here to be successful and by encouraging entrepreneurship. The country is growing, and a lot of the money parked by Indonesian businessmen abroad is coming back.   \par \par \uc2 I think the influx of funds started in 2002 and 2003. And as Indonesia continues to grow and provide a more conducive environment, you will see a lot more of that money coming back.   \par \par \uc2 But I think the way to attract the money is not to say, "Hey, bring your money back". I think the way to attract it is to say, "Hey, look, we are going to have 6-7 percent growth and people are making more money here".   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060313e23d00011\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
