\par\par \b \uc2 ADB forecasts RI growth slowdown due to high inflation  \b0\par\par\uc2 Urip Hudiono , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta  \par \uc2 572 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 April 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to continue slowing down this year, the Asian Development Bank (ADB) said Thursday, with high inflation and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  still battering consumption and private investments.  \par \par \uc2 The forecast of 5.4 percent growth, which is lower than the 5.6 percent achieved last year, puts Southeast Asia's largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  slightly behind the region's projected 5.5 percent average, and Asia's 7.2 percent.  \par \par \uc2 The government is expecting growth to reach 6.2 percent this year and 6.4 percent in 2007, while \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) sees 2006's full-year growth between 5.0 and 5.7 percent, with 4.58 percent growth during the first quarter.  \par \par \uc2 "Growth in the first half of 2006 will be constrained by soft private consumption demand owing to interest rate increases, high inflation and a likely rise in unemployment," the Manila-based lender said in its annual Asian Development Outlook (ADO) report.  \par \par \uc2 Exports are expected to remain slow as well, ADB local economist Amanah Abdulkadir added, with limited new investments curbing manufacturers from increasing their capacity, productivity and competitiveness in the global market.  \par \par \uc2 Significant amounts of investments -- particularly for infrastructure development -- are essential if Indonesia wishes to reach higher growth, ADB chief economist Ramesh Subramanian said, suggesting the government should improve the country's financial sector to tap the potentially large investment resources from the private sector in insurance and pension funds.  \par \par \uc2 Although Indonesia's investment climate has been improving, it is still deficient, the ADB noted in its report, as it urged the government to implement its own investment \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  package to reduce legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 The ADB in December forecast Indonesia's gross domestic product (GDP) to be able to grow between 5.8 to 6 percent as overall consumption -- which slumped after last year's fuel price hike -- recovered amid easing inflation and higher \b \highlight22\uc2 public spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 It revised the figure down because it expects inflation in the first half of 2006 to remain high because of implemented or planned increases in administered prices, minimum wages and government employee salaries.  \par \par \uc2 The bank projected inflation at around 14 percent, although it may moderate to 8 percent by the end of the year, with the effects of the fuel price hike wearing out, and to further slow in 2007.  \par \par \uc2 With this slower inflation, along with easing \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the ADB predicted Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth would be able to reach 6 percent in 2007.  \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  also is expected to counteract weaknesses in growth through increased \b \highlight22\uc2 public spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , a shift in \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  to regions and the move away from fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  to better-targeted \b \highlight22\uc2 public spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 "The main generator for growth in 2006 and 2007 will be domestic demand, stimulated primarily by \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures," ADB said.  \par \par \uc2 "The increased \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  allowed by the reduced fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  will have both direct and multiplier effects on growth, whose size depends on the availability and condition of infrastructure in the regions, and the effectiveness of local governments in implementing projects."  \par \par \uc2 Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook 2006-2007: <br> ..........................2004...2005...2006...2007<br> GDP growth (%, y-o-y).....5.1....5.6....5.4....6.0<br> Inflation (%, y-o-y)......6.5....17.1...14.0...7.5<br> Current account balance...1.2....1.1....1.0....0.9<br> (% of GDP)<br> Source: Asian Development Bank (ADB)  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060407e24700006\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
