\par\par \b \uc2 Death sentence not a solution but a problem  \b0\par\par\uc2 Frans H. Winarta , Jakarta  \par \uc2 662 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 April 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Three men sentenced to death by a court in Poso, Central Sulawesi, continue to proclaim their innocence. They are Fabianus Tibo, Marinus Riwu and Dominggus da Silva, all convicted of the murder of around 200 Muslims during clashes between religious groups in Poso in 2001.  \par \par \uc2 All legal measures have been taken against the decision; the three convicts filed for a case review with the Supreme Court and requested a pardon from President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, but to no avail. The families of the three prisoners made a second request for presidential pardon but were again rejected.  \par \par \uc2 The only legal avenue remaining is for the lawyers of the three to ask President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono to commute the death sentences to life in prison. This is the prerogative of the president, provided for in the Clemency Law. The president can utilize this privilege to commute death sentences, which are contrary to the Constitution and human rights. If President Yudhoyono chose to do this, it would ease the tension in Poso.  \par \par \uc2 As a nation based on Pancasila ideology, in which humanity is one of the five pillars, the concept of capital punishment as a deterrence must be eliminated if Indonesia wants to be considered a civilized society.  \par \par \uc2 The right to life is a basic right of every individual and cannot be annihilated by anybody else, including a powerful ruler, be he a king, emperor, president, prime minister, army general or dictator. They are not entitled to rob someone of his or her life.  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia must not embrace the death penalty in its criminal justice system, not only because it is inhumane, but also because it runs counter to our Constitution. The right to life is guaranteed and protected by the Constitution, particularly as far as Article 28 is concerned. Therefore, the new Criminal Code should not adopt the death penalty. Nowhere in the world has it been proven that the death penalty significantly reduces the crime rate. Instead, it has created endless \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  debate.  \par \par \uc2 The fate of the there prisoners on death row in Poso now depends very much on President Yudhoyono, who has the prerogative to accept, turn down or commute their death sentences. They must now be living in great \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which is of course torturous.  \par \par \uc2 This situation was best described in a 1950s Hollywood movie, I Want To Live , starring Susan Hayward. She played a woman facing execution in Texas for murder. She almost received a pardon from the governor, but the movie had an unhappy ending as she died in the electric chair. The tension she experienced, the emotions of a prisoner receiving conflicting messages on her fate during her last days, the tragedy of a mother facing execution and saying good-bye to her young daughter are worth considering by those who advocate the death penalty.  \par \par \uc2 Tibo and company were accused of masterminding the massacres in Poso, so they should have stood trial at a human rights tribunal, not in an ordinary court. The mass killings fall into the category of crimes against humanity. This is clearly stated in the Roman Statute.  \par \par \uc2 The fact that Indonesia has ratified the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, the International Covenant on Social, \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Cultural Rights and the UN Convention Against Torture, Cruel, Inhuman and Degrading Treatment means the death penalty must not be imposed on these three prisoners or any other prisoners here. Only the President can now save their lives by commuting their sentences. Slowly but surely Indonesia must embrace human rights in its new Criminal Code.  \par \par \uc2 Proponents of human rights are increasing their protests against the death sentences for the three men in Poso, and they expect their efforts to bear fruit. The question now is whether the President is willing to exercise his right to commute the sentences.  \par \par \uc2 The writer is a Jakarta-based human rights lawyer and member of the National Law Commission.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060415e24f0000w\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Minister of Finance: It is Difficult to Have  \highlight22\uc2 Economic \highlight\uc2  Growth of 6.2%  \b0\par\par\uc2 269 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 April 2006\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 Bisnis Indonesia  \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: Minister of Finance Sri Mulyani Indrawati revealed that it was difficult to have the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth target of 6.2% as targeted in 2006 due to the soaring international crude oil price and the low absorption of the State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  2006 funds.  \par \par \uc2 The government, she said, faced an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Nevertheless, she added, the government would not lower the assumption \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the Revised State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  2006.  \par \par \uc2 "This is an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  for 2006," she stated yesterday.  \par \par \uc2 The inflation rate, she explained, was estimated to decline, while the international \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  tended to increase.  \par \par \uc2 She further exposed that despite the possible increase in the international \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Indonesia still had rooms to lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 Sri continued that Indonesia would benefit from the capital inflow, especially the short-term ones.  \par \par \uc2 Next year, she inserted, the government might assume the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 6.4% in the State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  Draft 2007.  \par \par \uc2 Sri Mulyani admitted that it was difficult to meet the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth target of 6.2% since the declining economies in the last two quarters of 2005 still dragged on the the current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.  \par \par \uc2 In addition, she said, the disbursement of State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  2006 funds was still slow due to the tight \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  monitoring process.  \par \par \uc2 In the meantime, State Minister/Head of the National Development Planning Agency (Bappenas) Paskah Suzetta said the government would be more wisely to use funds in the State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  in efforts to compensate for the high oil \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  caused by the soaring international crude oil price. (Bisnis/06)  \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020060418e24i00004\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
