\par\par \b \uc2 Darmin faces tough job reforming  \highlight22\uc2 tax \highlight\uc2  office   \b0\par\par\uc2 Rendi Akhmad Witular , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 988 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 May 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 14\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Finance Minister Sri Mulyani Indrawati's appointment of her long-time colleague Darmin Nasution as the new director general of \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  could be seen as sign of her distrust toward most bureaucrats at the ministry.   \par \par \uc2 In her efforts to reform the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  office, which has long been seen as the country's most corrupt institution, Mulyani understands well that she cannot expect much of Darmin in terms of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  knowledge, other than his integrity.   \par \par \uc2 Integrity is just what Mulyani needs to fix the agency at a time when most of its troubled officials have allegedly embarked on intense lobbying with parties close to power, seeking higher positions or to at least to be spared a demotion.   \par \par \uc2 Having known Darmin since the 1970s, Mulyani acknowledges his sternness towards corruption during his career as the Finance Ministry's director general of financial institutions and as chairman of the capital market supervisory agency (Bapepam).   \par \par \uc2 Several of the ministry's officials recalled how Darmin, as director general of financial institutions, dared to reject a senior minister's request for collusion during the administration of former President Megawati Soekarnoputri.   \par \par \uc2 The minister, who now happens to be in a more senior post, asked Darmin to issue a guarantee letter for turnpike projects handled by local private companies linked with the minister and his family.   \par \par \uc2 Despite this successful history, however, Darmin was helpless in dealing with officials at Bapepam.