\par\par \b \uc2 Part 1 of 2: Democracy requires new strategies   \b0\par\par\uc2 Wisaksono Noeradi , Jakarta   \par \uc2 687 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 May 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's present problems are a result of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis that hit Asia in mid-1997 when, one by one, Thailand, Indonesia, and South Korea fell victim to the crisis and came to face serious \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Unlike the other two, Indonesia has yet to recover, despite the best intentions and efforts of Indonesians, global financial institutions, and international aid agencies. It hasn't been for want of trying, but it should be recognized that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis also triggered political and other problems. These in turn touched off major changes unprecedented in Indonesia's history.   \par \par \uc2 What were the new realities brought into the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector by reformasi ?   \par \par \uc2 Obviously, the monetary crisis brought revolutionary changes into the lives of Indonesians which were hard for the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector to believe, never mind accept. All of a sudden we saw political reforms that introduced real democracy. The implementation of regional decentralization also brought a lot of confusion and frustration.   \par \par \uc2 As \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  security became the sole responsibility of the police, the military's duty became handling defense matters and providing assistance in emergency situations only. Suddenly, the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector had to adopt new values. They were simply not prepared for the new realities. Yet, the show must go on.   \par \par \uc2 What has the Indonesian experience been? Since the monetary crisis, no political institution in Indonesia has suffered a greater crisis of legitimacy than the military. Theorists argue that civil-military reform is a critical component of democratization. Yet, many Indonesians credit the military with a role in the founding of the Republic, and therefore tolerate its often-violent approach to quelling conflict in troubled areas.   \par \par \uc2 The military has had to return to its principal role as the nation's defense force, and cease to be the tool of any political party as it was before reformasi when it sided with Golkar in the contest for political power. It should never again meddle in the affairs of the civilian government nor be involved in issues that are not related to national defense. Critics further argued that the dwi-fungsi (dual function) doctrine had become the military justification for involving itself in every aspect of running the country: politics, social control, economics, and security, both internal and external.   \par \par \uc2 On top of that, it has been predicted that the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  will show more courage in criticizing the military for repressive measures it took against civilians, especially during the New Order era. There may be calls to account for such excesses.   \par \par \uc2 On the other hand, the military has readily accepted an end to kekaryaan (temporary duty), a system that placed military officers in civil posts; in fact, many within the armed forces were convinced that this was in the interest of improving professionalism within the civil service. Another early step taken by the military on its own initiative was to cut formal ties with Golkar and adopt a strictly neutral position in elections.   \par \par \uc2 These new challenges required empowering internal stakeholders, rather than permitting them to revert to their former authoritarian practices. The military undertook several reforms in response to criticism.   \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, there was a continuing seesawing of \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  on the military's withdrawal from formal politics.   \par \par \uc2 It has been predicted that civil-military reform will call for the conversion of all TNI-owned enterprises into state-owned businesses, having all of them audited by independent auditors, and strengthening the political party system and civilian political institutions. Other demands include reviewing and revamping all \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  that "condones halfhearted civilian control over the TNI," and revising the security doctrine that governs the TNI.   \par \par \uc2 In short, the internal stakeholders have to be continuously reminded that the TNI has to "retreat to the barracks", and abandon its dual-function doctrine which guaranteed it a paramount role in politics.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is Vice Chairman of Matari Inc., Jakarta and can be reached at wisaksono@matari-ad.com. The article is a condensed version of his paper presented at the \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Relations for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Sector International Conference 2006 on April 24-25 in Kuala Lumpur.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060519e25j0000s\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
