\par\par \b  \highlight22\uc2 Policy \highlight\uc2 -making changes in the era of 'reformasi'  \b0\par\par\uc2 Kahlil Rowter , Jakarta  \par \uc2 1,153 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 May 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Almost a decade since the crisis that hit Indonesia in mid-1997, unlike Korea and Thailand, we have yet to witness previous \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth levels.  \par \par \uc2 It is true that, unlike those two countries, Indonesia also underwent profound political changes. But, since 2002, the political situation has stabilized. The fundamental question now is, is Indonesia, under the current politico-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  framework, doomed to a low \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth path?  \par \par \uc2 What has changed dramatically in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  structure? Since 1993, we have seen a dramatic increase in exports and imports. Looking at sector by sector, the structure has not changed a lot over the last 15 years. However, in the last five years, the main engine of growth has been the services-related sectors, including trade, hospitality, transportation and communications and financial services.  \par \par \uc2 These sectors have low employment elasticity, which means recent growth has created fewer jobs than before the crisis. It is also less equitable as ownership and employment in these sectors are concentrated in large cities, particularly Greater Jakarta.  \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 -making institutions have also undergone significant changes with an independent \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  and only a small part of \b \highlight22\uc2 public expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  under direct central government control, along with divestiture of \b \highlight22\uc2 public spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  to regional governments. An independent \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  and a floating exchange rate should provide a better banking sector governance and better inflationary management. But both also have associated costs.  \par \par \uc2 Improving banking sector governance entails a transition period when structures are put in place and human capital accumulates. Floating the exchange rate to allow better inflation management also entails a transition period until \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  agents become familiar with and able to handle volatility.  \par \par \uc2 For an open \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  like Indonesia's exchange rate pass-through is substantial, hence a volatile exchange rate creates additional \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  through other variables. The absence of a deep hedging market further exacerbates this situation.  \par \par \uc2 The small development \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  controlled by the central government created its own problem. In place of a centralized development effort we would have expected a well coordinated plan executed by the center alongside regional governments. But this has not materialized and it appears regional governments have different goals that do not necessarily add up to a well-thought out whole.  \par \par \uc2 As I have argued before ( The Jakarta Post Aug. 19, 2005), as most local governments are controlled by national parties it should be possible to make them toe the national line.  \par \par \uc2 Having oversight of the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is one thing, but having the legislature micro-manage decision-making is quite another. Furthermore, recruiting Cabinet members from important parties does not always mean the President can have his way. It may even entail a cost in terms of cohesion, particularly when facing tough cross-cutting issues. These party-spawned Cabinet members are first and foremost politicians seeking political capital and are not necessarily able or willing to carry out politically costly policies. Hence the most important and usually controversial decisions are handed back up to the President.  \par \par \uc2 An analogous case to regional development \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  not adding up to the whole development effort can also be argued to exist in other regional level policies that affect \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities.  \par \par \uc2 Examples abound on regional regulations that run counter to national level \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  direction. It is gratifying to learn that there is a concerted effort to overcome this. But this effort could easily run aground once faced with sweetheart deals or other high profile regional projects.  \par \par \uc2 It is easy to equate these two, but they are certainly distinct. Governance has been defined as how authority is gathered and exercised for \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  goals.  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia has made great strides in bringing to justice those who blatantly break the law. Yet, there remains a host of other corrupt -- but not illegal -- practices that are much more subtle and difficult to prosecute but just as, or even more, harmful. But even when anticorruption procedures have been put in place and watchdogs are unleashed, there remains the much broader challenge of governance.  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia has made great strides in the selection, monitoring and replacement of political leadership, which forms the first dimension of governance. Next we must strive for the second governance dimension: An effective government. This is our greatest challenge now. Examples abound on this very weakness. The result is that Indonesia faces a crisis in the third dimension of governance: Respect of citizens and the government for the country's institutions. Respect starts with trust, and we are not even here yet.  \par \par \uc2 Respect for institutions promotes efficiency. This is because \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  can achieve its goals simply by being announced. This is the credibility angle. Furthermore, respect also lowers transaction costs -- mainly the costs of monitoring -- and reduces \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Ultimately, in the case of corruption, respect promotes deterrence, which naturally lower the incidence of corruption and its attendant costs.  \par \par \uc2 Recent inflows into the financial market strengthened the rupiah and increased foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 . One explanation is the high interest differentials and at the same time the expected downward path in \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  (on the back of declining inflation) promises a potential upside for bond investors.  \par \par \uc2 This removed awkward questions on state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  sustainability and the inefficient use of resources. Even prior to this move investments in financial institutions took place, as a vote of confidence on reforms in this sector. Another boost to confidence was the settlement of the Cepu oil block.  \par \par \uc2 Now is the time to stop focusing only on fighting corruption and enlarge the focus to governance. Besides stifling creativity and even normal processes by instilling fear in the people carrying out just about any procedure, focusing only on anticorruption could hamper the anticorruption drive itself. For one thing it diverts attention away from addressing the underlying causes of corruption, and additionally it can even create opportunities for other forms of corruption in the future. An anticorruption drive should not be used only to show that something is being done.  \par \par \uc2 For proper governance to start, the key is to increase government \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  effectiveness and next to aim at trust and respect for institutions and processes. Coherence in \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 -making, with simple and easy to understand but concrete steps will be needed. In order to increase credibility, one key component is transparency.  \par \par \uc2 In this regard, the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  disclosure of the incomes and assets of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials is needed along with credible and more frequent audits. It is probably a good idea to create a national salary standard for \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials. Lastly, regular governance, anticorruption and \b \highlight22\uc2 public expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  surveys will improve trust and credibility. The old adage "trust but verify" may provide guidance.  \par \par \uc2 If these reforms are conducted the current favorable financial conditions will continue and spill over to the real sector creating a more equitable growth. Otherwise, Indonesia should expect a prolonged slow growth.  \par \par \uc2 The writer is a lecturer at the University of Indonesia's School of Economics. The views expressed are his own.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060522e25m0000g\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
