\par\par \b \uc2 Employment growth and changing market demands  \b0\par\par\uc2 Winarno Zain , Jakarta  \par \uc2 966 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 May 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's epidemic of social conflict has spread into the industrial relations area. If the tensions between employers and employees cannot be managed properly, the effect on employment growth could be serious. As the cost of labor rises as a relative share of production costs and peaceful industrial relations become rarer and rarer, it is not surprising that industries are turning to machines over labor in manufacturing.  \par \par \uc2 This movement away from labor means it will be extremely difficult for industries to absorb all the new workers coming to the market at the current projected gross domestic product growth rate. This means even if investment picks up later in the year, the unemployment rate of 10.3 percent will persist for some time to come.  \par \par \uc2 This gloomy employment picture can be seen in figures released by the Capital Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM). From 2001 to 2005, BKPM issued permanent licenses for 3634 projects, of which 80 percent are projects under foreign investment schemes. These projects require only 951,000 workers. In the meantime, during those 5 years, 10 million new workers entered the labor market.  \par \par \uc2 Foreign investments in Indonesia do not help much in absorbing labor, as they operate mainly in the chemical, pharmaceutical and paper industries, which are capital intensive. This explains why the number of jobs created by each dollar of investment has declined significantly since the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis in 1998. Last year only 18 jobs were created by each US$1 million invested, down from 29 jobs in 2001.  \par \par \uc2 There are a number of reasons why industries are moving away from labor-intensive methods of production.  \par \par \uc2 First, the enforcement of minimum wage regulations by the government has pushed up labor costs considerably. Since the autonomy laws took effect, local governments have implemented minimum wage increases with such vigor in their regions, for understandable political reasons. Minimum wages have been increased at rates exceeding inflation.  \par \par \uc2 These are the reasons behind steep rises in real wages in 2001 and 2003. The trend for significant increases in minimum wages has not stopped. The provincial government of Jakarta has just increased the regional minimum wage (UMR) for 2006 to Rp 816.000 ($93) per month, or an increase of 30 percent, well above the current inflation rate of 17 percent. At these rates, it is difficult for export industries like textiles to compete against exporters from other countries such as Bangladesh, Pakistan and Vietnam, where average wages are still $40-45 per month.  \par \par \uc2 According to the SMERU Research Institute in Jakarta, the employment elasticity of minimum wages in Indonesia is 0.1, meaning that for every 10 percent increase in UMR, employment shrinks by 1 percent, as companies reduce their number of workers.  \par \par \uc2 Secondly, globalization has forced Indonesian companies to reduce costs, and with advances in technology it is getting cheaper to replace workers with machines. Globalization has also opened up opportunities for Indonesian companies, especially in the textile and automotive parts industries, to set up factories overseas in low wage countries like Vietnam and China. Because of globalization, Indonesia -- in effect -- has been exporting jobs to other countries, at a time when job creation at home is still difficult.  \par \par \uc2 Finally, the introduction of the 2003 Manpower Law, affording more protection and security to workers at the expense of businesses, has made the labor market even more inflexible.  \par \par \uc2 In addition, the growing militancy of labor unions has undermined industrial relations, threatening the stability of management-worker relations at the factory level. In these \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  times, nothing is more important for the management of a factory than peaceful relations with their workers.  \par \par \uc2 To ease unemployment is necessary to quickly develop industries that have high labor absorption rates. The BKPM list shows that food crops, plantations and the forestry industry have very high labor absorption rates. Developing these sectors could provide a significant number of new jobs, but such development could also face some constraints, especially in the forestry and plantation industries. Plantations also require huge amounts of long term investment, financing that is not readily available.  \par \par \uc2 Notwithstanding their steep rise this year, prices of primary commodities in international market are historically volatile and less stable than those of industrial products. However, the biggest constraints are conservation-based.  \par \par \uc2 The government \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to expand resource-based industries has met resistance from environmental groups, and it is getting more difficult to strike a balance between the development of these industries and the need for natural conservation. Exploiting the still available opportunities for agro-industrial development will require an improved regulatory framework and more vigorous law enforcement.  \par \par \uc2 Small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) are an important source of employment in Indonesia. They account for 55 percent of all employment, according to data from the Central Statistics Agency. As such, it is imperative that the government streamline its policies to allow more rapid growth for SMEs.  \par \par \uc2 The growth of SMEs still faces many hurdles. Business regulations issued by 400 local governments are becoming more onerous and hinder the growth and operation of SMEs. SMEs also have problems accessing capital, as the market for microfinance has yet to be developed. The restriction of outsourcing in the current labor law also hampers their, as the bulk of subcontractors are SMEs. Lifting the sub-contracting restrictions from the current law would allow the successful integration of SMEs into dynamic manufacturing sectors, thus opening up more employment opportunities.  \par \par \uc2 However, the above measures are only supplementary to the overall \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  needed to improve the investment climate. This can only be achieved if all the basic elements -- a strong macro \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  base, legal certainty, better infrastructure, and good governance -- are in place.  \par \par \uc2 The writer is a Jakarta-based \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  analyst. He can be reached at winarno_zain@yahoo.com.sg.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060524e25o0000j\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
