\par\par \b \uc2 Financial markets await direction of U.S. rates  \b0\par\par\uc2 The Jakarta Post , Jakarta  \par \uc2 709 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 June 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's stock market is expected to follow on the sentiments of other bourses in the region for the coming week, analysts said, with the rupiah being largely dependent as well on the local market's upcoming performance.  \par \par \uc2 "Regional and global factors will still play a dominant role in determining where our local market will be heading, analyst Fendi Susiyanto of Permata Bank told The Jakarta Post on Sunday. "Investors are in particular waiting for certainty in the trend of the U.S. Federal Reserve rates, and watching out for the still volatile world oil prices."  \par \par \uc2 Speaking of local sentiments, Fendi mentioned May's higher inflation data, which may add to the pressure on \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's (BI) rate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 "The market will also be waiting for BI's response to all of this -- both towards the inflation and the latest global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation," he said.  \par \par \uc2 Counting in these two main factors, Fendi sees the market to test a resistance of 1,371 points for the week, with support seen at 1,291.  \par \par \uc2 Shares in the infrastructure, mining and agriculture sectors are expected to support trading, while those in the financial and manufacturing being vulnerably volatile.  \par \par \uc2 "The market's index may experience a large swing if sentiments indeed drive it into negative territory," he said.  \par \par \uc2 Dealers forecast the bourse to start off the week on relatively flat trading, ahead of BI's next \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  meeting on Tuesday.  \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Stock Exchange Composite Index ended higher last Friday to 1,347.686 points, up 26.126 points or 1.97 percent from its closing the previous day.  \par \par \uc2 It had gained 24.539 points or 1.85 percent over the week, its first weekly advance in three, although it still wobbled between 1,366.17 high on Tuesday and a 1,321.56 low on Thursday. Average daily volume was 1.42 billion shares worth Rp 1.75 trillion ($190 million).  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's rupiah, meanwhile, was also firmer against the U.S. dollar, ending up last Friday by a slight 0.7 percent to Rp 9,260 a dollar. It had gained 1.2 percent over the week along with other regional monies.  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's key index had indeed mostly followed in the steps of other Asian markets last week, particularly of Tokyo's Nikkei 225 index. Hongkong's Hang Seng, Korea's KOSPI, as well as Taiwan, Singapore and Thailand's bourses also rose on rebounds and overnight gains in New York's Wall Street from promising U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  data.  \par \par \uc2 Investors' further analysis of the data may however throw off their earlier confidence over the American \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as they again doubt its impact towards the Fed to end its 16-month rate hike cycle to 5 percent. Wall Street is still concerned as well about recent \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in global energy prices, all of whose effects may propagate to regional bourses.  \par \par \uc2 A still tight Fed rate, coupled with Indonesia's higher May inflation data, may affect BI's recent rate cut \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to support \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, despite BI Governor Burhanuddin Abdullah remaining upbeat on continuing the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  had cut its key BI rate to 12.5 percent last month, after raising it from 8.5 in July to 12.75 percent by December, and kept them unchanged since, to contain a surge in inflation due to last year's fuel price hikes.  \par \par \uc2 Higher inflation and rates affect company prospects from weakening \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  consumption and their ability to expand their businesses. A weaker rupiah, meanwhile, makes their raw material imports and debt servicing costlier.  \par \par \uc2 Analyst Farial Anwar of the Currency Management Group said the rupiah will largely be determined by the volatility in the local stock market over the week.  \par \par \uc2 "It is currently at some Rp 9,300 a dollar, but may swing to between Rp 9,000 and Rp 9,200, or between Rp 9,400 and Rp 9,500, according to the market's performance this week," he said.  \par \par \uc2 There was a tendency for the rupiah to weaken, Farial explained, as investors doubt the local stock market's ability to reach 1,500 points again, therefore driving them more towards profit-taking this week.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060605e26500014\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
