\par\par \b \uc2 Helping tsunami survivors without land  \b0\par\par\uc2 Muamar Vebry, Contributor, Banda Aceh  \par \uc2 876 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 June 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 When the devastating tsunami had at last subsided, Joharini Pidie was one of the lucky ones. The widow with two children ran for her life when waves as high as coconut trees hit Tibang, a gampong (village) one kilometer from the beach in Banda Aceh.  \par \par \uc2 By early February 2005, more than a month after the nearly-apocalyptic tsunami, the village-dwellers, led by the geucik (head of the village), had returned. They regained their seaman's spirit once they saw the coastline. Now they nurture growing hopes of rebuilding their lives. Locals agreed that if aid ever came, priority would go to those who had returned early, and who still had a plot of land left by the tsunami. Joharini was among those early birds, but she was just a renter. When a non-governmental organization put her on its list to receive a house, many protested.  \par \par \uc2 It is difficult to determine the rights of renters because they did not own the land or houses they used to live in. But, like the landlords, the renters lost nearly everything they owned. It is clear that renters have the right to as much aid as landlords get.  \par \par \uc2 The Aceh and Nias Reconstruction and Rehabilitation Agency (BRR) and UN-Habitat held a \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  consultation on Sept. 22, 2005. The participants concluded that the position of survivors who were renters is very \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . One group of residents said they had reached the point of desperation because they were excluded from meetings held by their geucik to discuss the distribution of aid. Those survivors were seen as having no right to assistance. Meanwhile, the government's draft plan also did not detail the kind of aid survivors without a house or land would get. The draft specified that renters were eligible to get houses, but it did not clarify whether they would get land.  \par \par \uc2 A survivor like Joharini Pidie must struggle against obstacles such as the stigma of being a renter, in addition to all the other psychological pressures survivors are experiencing. Fortunately, she had bought a plot of land near her rented house, so she got assistance.  \par \par \uc2 There are thousands of renters, however, who did not own land and lost all their possessions in the tsunami. This became a complicated problem for BRR, and the draft plan did not provide adequate guidelines. To add to the headaches, many institutions in the country are inexperienced at addressing problems like these.  \par \par \uc2 There are no official records on the number of renters and the exact locations of rented houses in Aceh or other provinces. There was a lack of statistics on the number of renters even before the tsunami, and this became a serious hurdle in the government's efforts to estimate the number of people who were eligible for aid. It is ironic that Indonesia has accurate statistics on the number of chickens throughout districts and the number of eggs they produce, but does not know how many people rent houses.  \par \par \uc2 At this point, it is urgent for BRR to try an "experiment" and aim for a breakthrough to resolve the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The agency must identify and provide applicable solutions. Aid for survivors who were renters prior to the tsunami is relatively more complicated compared to those whose houses were devastated. The most complex problem is where the houses for the landless survivors will be built.  \par \par \uc2 A clear \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  for renters  \par \par \uc2 UN-Habitat has launched a number of experiments, including one at Keramat village in Banda Aceh. The objective of this test case was to solve the problems faced by renters. One solution was to provide victims assistance to build houses if they had land somewhere else. Another was to rebuild their former rental houses with guarantees from the landlords that they could live in the houses for seven years rent-free.  \par \par \uc2 Another experiment was carried out in Punge Jurong, where there were over 100 families listed as renters.  \par \par \uc2 BRR is expected to issue a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to ensure that renters will have houses. To accomplish this, BRR could help renters obtain land in their original communities. The aid could also take the form of a special loan to purchase land, with a grace period before the first payment is due. It's recommended that the monthly rent be no more than it was before the tsunami.  \par \par \uc2 Such polices would support the survivors' \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social reconstruction process in the communities where they rented.  \par \par \uc2 As of April 2006, there were only 19,483 units of housing completed in Aceh, with 21,997 still under construction. This speed of reconstruction has caused many people to conclude that the target of building 100,000 new houses and rehabilitating 80,000 damaged ones, including those in Nias, cannot be reached before mid-2007. However, BRR's strong determination, reflected in their initial plan to finish 78,000 units of housing by the end of 2006, as well as the improving security situation on the ground, could accelerate the distribution of housing assistance to victims, regardless of their status as landlords or renters. ***  \par \par \uc2 The writer is a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  program manager at UN-Habitat, Banda Aceh. This article does not necessarily reflect the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of the organization.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060611e26b00006\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36