\par\par \b \uc2 Toll operator wants revolving fund for land clearance   \b0\par\par\uc2 Benget Simbolon Tnb. , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 604 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 June 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The government should create a mechanism of land freezing and a revolving fund to finance land clearances, which are often the main hurdle to infrastructure developments, a top official from toll road operator PT. Jasa Marga has said.   \par \par \uc2 Speaking at a seminar Wednesday on financing infrastructure developments, the state-owned toll road investor and operator PT. Jasa Marga's President Director, Frans S. Sunito, said a land freezing mechanism should disallow land transactions in certain areas after the government announces plans to build infrastructure there.   \par \par \uc2 "Land transactions then can only be done by the original land owners before the government makes an announcement," Frans said, adding such a mechanism would help cut down on the use of middle men and land brokers in every infrastructure project.   \par \par \uc2 He said the government would finance such land clearance with a revolving fund specially designed for infrastructure developments.   \par \par \uc2 "For a start a total fund of about Rp 2 trillion (US$222.2 million) is enough. Then through a revolving mechanism its amount will snowball as later investors will be required to pay back the used fund plus interest prevailing at the market rate," he said.   \par \par \uc2 Frans also suggested setting up an independent team of land appraisers to decide real land prices.   \par \par \uc2 "The independent appraisers will trace the historical prices of the land. They then will decide the land price that has to be paid by the government," he said.   \par \par \uc2 As making a new law will take a long time, he urged the government to just issue a Perpu (a government \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  in lieu of law) on the infrastructure, as it would not require the government to present it to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) for deliberation.   \par \par \uc2 He said all steps were necessary to hasten the development of the infrastructure the country needs to stimulate the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Poor infrastructure has long become the main obstacle to drawing new investments to Indonesia, which has only seen \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of between three and five percent -- not enough to reduce the increasing unemployment rate -- since the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis in 1997.   \par \par \uc2 Frans said land clearance for road construction projects averaged at about 30 percent of the total cost. "But due to the land problem, the cost can end up being more than 100 percent up from what was originally estimated."   \par \par \uc2 "Look at the construction of JORR (the Jakarta Outer Ring Road), as an example. Its total costs have increased more than 100 percent from what we had estimated due to the problem of land clearances," he said.   \par \par \uc2 "Once in certain sections, the original price was only Rp 800,000 per meter. But then due to the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and many land brokers we had to pay up to Rp 10 million per meter."   \par \par \uc2 Sigit Pramono, the president director of the state-owned bank BNI, agreed with Frans, saying the land problem had often discouraged banks from investing money in developing infrastructure.   \par \par \uc2 "We often hear or read in the media that banks have no money to finance infrastructure. But I tell you, the truth is we have the money. But the land problem makes us reluctant to release the funds we've promised," he said.   \par \par \uc2 He said BNI had committed some Rp 6 trillion to financing infrastructure developments over the next five years.   \par \par \uc2 But he said banks also faced problems matching their available short term funds with the long term nature of infrastructure developments.   \par \par \uc2 "We banks, therefore, have to find alternatives to financing the infrastructure developments. The alternatives include issuing bonds or through the mechanism of rights issues," he said.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060615e26f00014\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
