\par\par \b \uc2 Analysts say markets to remain volatile this week  \b0\par\par\uc2 Urip Hudiono , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta  \par \uc2 562 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 June 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Local shares and the rupiah are expected to remain on a volatile edge this week, with analysts baffled in guessing their upcoming direction due to the fact that Indonesia's capital markets are still largely under the whim of global market trends.  \par \par \uc2 "It's still going to be a fragile and fluctuating week," market analyst Dandossi Matram told the Post on Sunday.  \par \par \uc2 "First there's the remaining \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  of the Fed rate, and then there's the persistent speculative nature of our markets."  \par \par \uc2 Dandossi said a more stable rupiah -- likely to be between Rp 9,200 and Rp 9,300 per U.S. dollar for the week -- could help reduce volatility in stock trading, but added the Jakarta Stock Exchange Composite Index may well experience a weaker trend again after strengthening above 1,300 points last week.  \par \par \uc2 "There may well be some profit taking in the making," he said, without mentioning the market's possible trading range.  \par \par \uc2 Jakarta's benchmark bourse had closed the week ending June 16 by jumping 67.875 points -- or 5.4 percent -- higher to 1,309.525 on Friday.  \par \par \uc2 The index had over the week gained an overall 2.7 percent, having seen along the way a 2.8 percent drop Tuesday.  \par \par \uc2 Average daily volume for the past week was 1.28 billion shares worth Rp 1.56 trillion ($166 million).  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's currency also ended the week at a firmer rate of Rp 9,305 level against the American greenback, from Thursday's Rp 9,390.  \par \par \uc2 The rupiah managed to strengthen by slight 1 percent for the whole week, despite reaching a Tuesday low of Rp 9,500 on the stock market volatility.  \par \par \uc2 Financial markets worldwide remained jittery from continued speculation that U.S. Federal Reserve chairman Ben Bernanke may lift rates again to curb a recent rise in the country's inflation.  \par \par \uc2 Friday's global market rally, however, came after Bernanke said the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could withstand lately higher energy and commodity prices, easing concerns of another Fed rate hike from its current 5 percent level.  \par \par \uc2 For local shares, positive sentiments also arose from \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) Governor Burhanuddin Abdullah, saying a further half percentage point rate cut towards Indonesia's 12.5 percent key rate was possible as inflation slowed.  \par \par \uc2 Lower domestic rates do good for company prospects and the whole \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . A too thin difference from global rates may however affect investors interest in local assets of shares, bonds and its currency.  \par \par \uc2 And analysts are doubting that the easing concerns over another rate hike may last long, with Bank International Indonesia chief economist Ferry Latuhihin being quoted by AFP as saying investors were still unfamiliar with Bernanke's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and could not predict his moves.  \par \par \uc2 "What matters most to investors is U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  but Bernanke is hard to predict because he is new. We don't know what he's going to say on Monday," he said.  \par \par \uc2 Analyst Farial Anwar of the Currency Management Group similarly said the local capital markets would unlikely take BI's latest statement for granted, being more driven by global market sentiments.  \par \par \uc2 He saw the rupiah trading from a strong Rp 9,200 and refraining from weakening beyond Rp 9,500, unless panic selling occurs in the market over the week.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST002