\par\par \b \uc2 Pushing bank lending   \b0\par\par\uc2 635 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 July 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  remains optimistic about meeting the 18 percent credit expansion target for the year, even though total lending rose a mere 2.4 percent during the first five months. But without concerted efforts to ease lending operations, the optimism voiced by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Deputy Governor Maman Somantri on Monday will prove groundless and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue to suffer from a punishing credit crunch.   \par \par \uc2 In fact, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was acutely short of lifeblood during the first semester, the result of limited credit expansion and very slow \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  disbursement, both by the central government and regional administrations.   \par \par \uc2 Finance Minister Sri Mulyani Indrawati acknowledged during a hearing with the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  last week that the realized development (investment) \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  during the first six months was only about 20 percent of the total amount budgeted for the entire \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year.   \par \par \uc2 The majority of the blame for the persistently slow credit expansion cannot be put on the tight monetary stance pursued by the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to address strong inflationary pressure, even though its benchmark short-term interest rate remains at over 12 percent.   \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  tried earlier this year to ease bank lending through a set of new measures designed to increase commercial banks' lending resources. The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  in late January eased the uniform classification of loan collectibility and the rating of credits to small and medium enterprises, enabling banks to reduce provisions for their loans and thereby increasing their funds available for lending.   \par \par \uc2 In fact, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  initially envisaged credit expansion this year even higher than last year's 21 percent increase to lubricate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities, yet not too high as to unnecessarily threaten a higher rate of nonperforming loans.   \par \par \uc2 Such an expansive credit program was badly needed to support the government's plan to provide \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the first semester through a 20 percent increase in investment \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including the disbursement of Rp 15-20 trillion (US$1.5-2 billion) in development funds carried over from 2005.   \par \par \uc2 However, the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  failed to materialize and new credit extension remained slow.   \par \par \uc2 We expected credit expansion to be much faster in the second quarter due to the weakening inflationary pressure since February and the strengthening of the rupiah to an average Rp 9,205 against the dollar in the first semester, compared to Rp 9,412 in the same period last year.   \par \par \uc2 But as these developments once again clearly showed, \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , inflation and exchange rates are not the main factors influencing the rate of credit expansion.   \par \par \uc2 State banks, which account for more than 60 percent of total bank lending, still seemed preoccupied with their high rate of nonperforming loans and were overly cautious about new lending.   \par \par \uc2 Moreover, it still seemed extremely difficult for banks to find bona fide, creditworthy companies. Business risks in the country also remain unusually high due to inadequate law enforcement, crumbling basic infrastructure, high logistics costs and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about bureaucratic procedures and the regulatory environment.   \par \par \uc2 Certainly, banks will prefer parking their funds in such risk-free money market instruments as the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's debt papers (SBI) to lending to businesses that are extremely vulnerable to financial distress and, consequently, loan defaults.   \par \par \uc2 We believe the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  has done its part to help ease the credit crunch, but it cannot be expected to significantly lower its benchmark short-term interest rate within a short period of time, because this could dampen portfolio investor interest in rupiah assets and cause speculative attacks on the currency.   \par \par \uc2 The government should work harder to do its part by reducing business risks through the accelerated implementation of reforms.   \par \par \uc2 Without significant improvement in the business climate, businesses will remain highly vulnerable to default. An environment of high credit risk will clearly make most banks inordinately conservative in their lending operations.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060712e27c0000h\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Composite Stock Index and Rupiah Exchange Rate Decline  \b0\par\par\uc2 514 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 July 2006\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 Bisnis Indonesia  \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: The soaring international oil price to US$78.40 per barrel has shocked the rupiah exchange rate against the US dollar and the Composite Stock Index, which declined by 2.28% at yesterday's trading.  \par \par \uc2 The world's crude oil price yesterday rose to US$78.05 per barrel at the New York Mercantile Exchange (Nymex), while the world's brent oil price soared to US$78.46 per barrel because of Israeli attacks to Lebanon and Syria.  \par \par \uc2 The soaring crude oil price has battered the Composite Stock Index at the Jakarta Stock Exchange (BEJ), which yesterday was closed at 1,303.58, down by 30.44 points or 2.28% from 1,334.02 on the previous day, which is the largest decline in the past month.  \par \par \uc2 In the meantime, some stock markets in Asia have also declined due to the soaring oil prices, the Japanese \b \highlight22\uc2 Central Bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  interest rate hike by 0.25%, and to the actions of raising prices made by some energy companies.  \par \par \uc2 The largest decline yesterday was suffered by BSE Sensex 30, which was by 171.98 points to 10,686.52, followed by Taiwan Taiex index that declined by 139.57 points.  \par \par \uc2 The soaring oil prices have also suppressed the rupiah exchange rate against the US dollar, which yesterday was down by 50 points to IDR9,215.  \par \par \uc2 According to BI Governor Burhanuddin Abdullah, the soaring oil prices could put more pressures on the rupiah exchange rate against the US dollar. "The soaring oil prices, the Fed rate hike, the dominance of short-term capital flow in the foreign currency market, and the limited long-term foreign currency supply, all of these have put pressures on the rupiah exchange rate," he informed during a working meeting with the House.  \par \par \uc2 Play down the effect of soaring oil prices  \par \par \uc2 However, Vice President Jusuf Kalla seemed to play down the importance of the soaring oil prices.  \par \par \uc2 "I just spoke with the Minister of Finance yesterday afternoon and I can assure you our state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  will not be affected even if the oil price soars to US$100 per barrel," he said yesterday.  \par \par \uc2 He added that the soaring oil prices would also increase the government's revenues. Therefore, he continued, the government would not apply another fuel price hike this year.  \par \par \uc2 On the other hand, Minister of Finance Sri Mulyani Indrawati was worried that the soaring crude oil price in the world would create \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 Coordinating Minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs Boediono also argued that the oil and gas revenues that the government would gain from the soaring oil prices would still be smaller than the \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  burden that the government had to bear.  \par \par \uc2 However, BI Deputy Governor Hartadi A. Sarwono and Aslim Tadjuddin stated that the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  was ready at any time to make intervention with the market to stabilize the rupiah. (04/Fahmi Achmad/Dwi Wahyuni) (pudji.lestari@bisnis.co.id; erna.girsang@bisnis.co.id)  \par \par \uc2 By Pudji Lestari & Erna S. U. Girsang  \par \par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia  \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020060717e27f00002\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Investors Return to Batam   \b0\par\par\uc2 463 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 July 2006\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 BATAM: At least eight Singaporean companies are going to make investments in Batam and Bintan following the signing of an agreement on June 25, 2006 between the Indonesian government and Singaporean government on the establishment of special \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  zones in the regions.   \par \par \uc2 The return of investors to Batam provides a breath of fresh air to improve the investment climate in the regions, which have been left by some investors due to legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the reapplication of VAT and sales \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  on luxurious goods since 2004.   \par \par \uc2 Governor of Riau Island Ismeth Abdullah revealed that eight Singaporean companies were going to realize around US$31.6 million in investment, which would be able to create 2,000 jobs.   \par \par \uc2 "We are going to sign a memorandum of understanding with the investors on August 1. We view that this is a good start for the establishment of special \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  zone and investment growth in the future," he said in Batam yesterday.   \par \par \uc2 According to Ismeth, seven companies would make US$18.3 million (around Sin$30 million) in investment in Batam. The companies specialize in, among others, ship repair and construction and cross transportation.   \par \par \uc2 Another investor, Tiong Won, was going to build an off-shore rig manufacturer with an investment of Sin$20 million (US$13.3 million) in Bintan. "They are expected to operate soon since there is no problem for them to get licenses from the province."   \par \par \uc2 Ismeth informed that the provincial government was going to conduct a trial of one stop service in Batam, Bintan, and Karimun start from July 25. "The trial will start at the same time with the Special \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Zone joint working group in Batam."   \par \par \uc2 Data by the Batam Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin Batam) revealed that in 2004-2005, at least eight companies had shut down operation in, or relocated businesses from, industrial regions in Batam, such as Sekupang, Batamindo Industrial Park, Megacipta Industrial Park, Malindo Industrial Park, and Walakaka Industrial Park.   \par \par \uc2 Infrastructure project   \par \par \uc2 To anticipate the return of investors to Batam and its surrounding, continued Ismeth, the Riau Provincial Government this year would start realizing some infrastructure projects, such as electricity, drinking water, road, and transportation infrastructures.   \par \par \uc2 He added that the airport expansion project would also start this year using funds from the Regional State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . "We will increaser the length of the runway at Karimun airport from 800 meters to 1,600 meters using funds from the State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Regional State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 ."   \par \par \uc2 Ismeth projected that Batam's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth would hit 8.2% in 2007. Last year, Batam's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  grew by 7.8%.   \par \par \uc2 "We hope Batam's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will grow by 8.2%-8.5% in 2007, while Riau's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in overall will increase by 6.5%." (Bisnis/hl)   \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020060724e27o0002t\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
