\par\par \b \uc2 S&P ups RI ratings on improving finances  \b0\par\par\uc2 Urip Hudiono , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta  \par \uc2 563 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 July 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia has stepped up the investment ladder again, with global credit rating agency Standard and Poor's (S&P) raising the country's sovereign ratings Wednesday on improving \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and balance of payments performances.  \par \par \uc2 S&P upped Indonesia's long-term foreign currency debt rating to "BB-" from "B+", and its local currency rating to "BB+" from "BB". The outlook on both ratings is "stable". S&P also affirmed Indonesia's short-term rating at "B".  \par \par \uc2 The upgrade puts Indonesian government dollar-denominated bond debt and overseas borrowings three rungs below the "BBB-" investment-grade rating, on a par with Turkey and Ukraine.  \par \par \uc2 The country's rupiah-based liabilities, meanwhile, are just one rung below the level at which investors can consider the country to have adequate financial capacity and resilience to repay its debts.  \par \par \uc2 A "stable" outlook means the rating is expected to hold in the long run. It may be revised up to a "positive" outlook prior to another rating upgrade in the near future.  \par \par \uc2 S&P last revised Indonesia's rating outlook upward in February, while other rating agencies have also signaled upbeat views about the country.  \par \par \uc2 Moody's Investment Services raised its foreign-currency rating on Indonesia to "B1" from "B2", which is the equivalent of just one rung below S&P's latest upgraded rating. Fitch Ratings, meanwhile, views Indonesia positively on a "BB-" rating.  \par \par \uc2 Higher ratings and positive outlooks reduce the risk-premium cost on borrowing. The government has upped its target of net proceeds from bond sales to help finance this year's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  to Rp 35.8 trillion (US$3.8 billion) from Rp 24.9 trillion previously.  \par \par \uc2 In its statement announcing the ratings upgrade, S&P noted Indonesia's declining debt-burden risk, with the government continuing to prudently manage its finances with a view to eventually achieving a balanced \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , despite the fact that this year's \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  is likely to rise to 1.2 percent of gross domestic product from the government's previous 0.7 percent estimate.  \par \par \uc2 The country has also managed to maintain small, yet persistent, current account surpluses and foreign direct investment (FDI) inflows, S&P credit analyst Sani Hamid said, with falling \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and a strengthening rupiah projected to lower the debt burden to under 50 percent of GDP this year from over 100 percent in 2000.  \par \par \uc2 The rupiah has gained 7.7 percent against the U.S. dollar this year, while first-half FDI inflows rose 4.8 percent to US$3.51 billion. The country's foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  stood at US$40.1 billion on June 30.  \par \par \uc2 S&P warned, however, of several factors constraining Indonesia from advancing further up the investment ladder, citing the government's past history of running unmanageably high external debt levels.  \par \par \uc2 A lack of transparency in the finances of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 -sector entities, lack of coordination between the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary authorities, and the ever-present problems of corruption, legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the infrastructure \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  and labor market rigidities could hamper improvements in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 "A faster implementation of reforms on \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , labor, infrastructure development and the legal structure, coupled with improved \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector transparency, would favorably influence the rating outlook on Indonesia," Sani said.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060727e27r00012\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
