\par\par \b \uc2 The European Union is not giving up   \b0\par\par\uc2 Peter Mandelson , Brussels   \par \uc2 629 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 July 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The suspension of negotiations in the WTO Doha Round is a painful blow for the global trading system. The potential costs of indefinite suspension are high, both politically and economically.   \par \par \uc2 It has dented the credibility of the WTO at a time of global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and geopolitical \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , when all states need to jointly harness globalization, in order to best take advantage of it and reap its benefits for the greatest number. Without the Doha Round, the WTO's central commitment to progressive trade liberalization and development through free and fair trade can only seem empty.   \par \par \uc2 Fundamentally, we were close to a package that is greater in value than anything ever achieved in previous trade rounds.   \par \par \uc2 During these negotiations, the EU was able to make a significant improvement in its agricultural market access offer, bringing its average cuts close to the level requested by the G20 group of developing countries, provided others move in parallel. I am glad the G20 were good enough to acknowledge our level of ambition may not be what some have demanded but I defy anyone to say that it is meager:   \par \par \uc2 o 100 percent elimination of export \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . For example, the EU will reduce its exports of sugar by 5 million tonnes, of fresh milk by 8 million tonnes. EU poultry exports would fall by a quarter;   \par \par \uc2 o 75 percent reduction in trade distorting domestic support;   \par \par \uc2 o Readiness to go to a 50 percent average \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut: For the developed world the EU has floated a further step from our existing tabled offer of 39 percent average farm \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  cuts to "close to" 51.5 percent. This is a substantial move, and by far the deepest farm \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  cuts the EU has ever offered in a multilateral negotiation;   \par \par \uc2 o We also indicated that we were ready to talk about the number and treatment of sensitive products: Sensitive product tariffs will be cut, and their \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate quota levels expanded to allow new market access.   \par \par \uc2 This is more, much more, than anyone would have expected from the EU.   \par \par \uc2 And the EU is not giving up on this Round. We have stuck with it, paid into it, and given a lot... We will continue to do so, because it is right and fair towards the developing world, as well as in our own \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  interests.   \par \par \uc2 While we work to get Doha back on track, Europe's trade agenda will inevitably have to move on. Europe will continue to explore the possibility of regional trade agreements with ASEAN and other countries. But these things are not alternatives to Doha or the multilateral system. No bilateral agreement can reproduce the global benefits of a multilateral deal. The WTO will remain the essential platform for ensuring Europe's interests and the interests of development are recognized in the global trading system. Bilateral and regional \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  can only complement that system.   \par \par \uc2 I believe that elements of the Doha negotiations related directly to development should be salvaged following the suspension of wider talks. We will not allow the poor countries to fall victim of it and we will suggest elaborating an early harvest package of development measures, to show our solidarity with and commitment to the development goals at the heart of the Doha Round.   \par \par \uc2 The EU would be willing to pursue specific proposals on Special and Differential Treatment on a stand alone basis. Aid for Trade and agreement on duty-free quota-free market access could also be pursued on a fast-track basis.   \par \par \uc2 I dearly hope that, when the smoke has cleared, others will want to do the same. The EU stands ready to carry on where we have left off.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is the European Commissioner for External Trade.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060729e27t0000j\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
