\par\par \b \uc2 Photography exhibition challenges art market  \b0\par\par\uc2 Carla Bianpoen , Contributor, Jakarta  \par \uc2 1,020 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 August 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 As photography is still grappling with its acceptance as a form of art and art collectors have barely given it a second thought, the Vanessa Art Link is challenging the art market by displaying photographs that she thinks should be given due consideration.  \par \par \uc2 Besides their extraordinary large-scale formats, the works made by eight photographers from China are truly striking.  \par \par \uc2 It is clear that China's rapid transformation into an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  superpower has had an indelible impact on its artists, spurring their impeccable skill, profound depth of concept, refined feeling and incredible ability to think innovatively.  \par \par \uc2 One is particularly struck by the extremes in technology, the pinhole on one hand, and advanced digital on the other, but both sharing a spirit of reinventing the old -- inventing the old into rarefied photographic art.  \par \par \uc2 The pinhole technique goes back to the earliest phases of photography. In fact the earliest mention of it was by Chinese philosopher Mo-Ti (fifth century BC) who formally recorded the creation of an inverted image formed by light rays passing through a pinhole into a darkened room.  \par \par \uc2 Could it be a coincidence that Shi Guorui decided to use the technique that German astronomer Johannes Keppler called camera obscura, or was it a deliberate decision? Whatever it was, Shi does not shrink back from hard efforts to recreate the old technique. He also does not mind \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  several months planning, because it is a technique that requires time. If there are no existing buildings or rooms to be used as his camera obscura, he will build one on site, which takes another additional few weeks before he gets into action. He also does not mind the fact that this technique only allows one print of each picture. In fact it makes his prints all the more exquisite.  \par \par \uc2 The print of Mt. Everest, for instance, which will be in this exhibition, had to be framed before being sent off to Indonesia. Surely a delicate matter, as it has a width of four meters and adequate framing here is not available. Vanessa revealed that with the packing, the parcel containing this single photograph weighs over a hundred kilograms. It won't be for sale, but Vanessa says she just wants to share her admiration for this oeuvre with the wider \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  here.  \par \par \uc2 Reinventing the old is also what Miao Xiaochun does, but contrary to Shi, he uses the most advanced technology. When pondering Michelangelo's masterpiece The Last Judgment , Miao wondered how the scene would be when looked at from the rear and the sides. He made a picture of his own body and put it in cyberspace replacing the 400 figures in Michelangelo's work and making them appear like sculptural versions. Miao had apparently firm views of his own about the principle of judgment, let alone the last judgment. For what is bad and what is good, what is high (heaven) and what is low (hell), he ponders. What looks prominent from the front view loses prominence when viewed from the rear or the side, or from below. Working out his imaginations and alternative views on what the last judgment entails by manipulating his identical bald-headed nudes in cyberspace produced large-scale scenes that are surreal, stirring and awe-inspiring.  \par \par \uc2 Other photographers concerned themselves with the passing of time, the changing of culture and with disappearing cultural icons of the past.  \par \par \uc2 The large photographs by Chen Jiagang and Zhu Yan, featuring a solitary tiny figure amid an overwhelmingly large field of vision, express profound melancholy at what was and what is to come, with colors of dusk putting an accent on the mood.  \par \par \uc2 Icons of culture tend to disappear with the changing of the guards, be it political, social or otherwise, but they are part of an era that must not be erased. He Chongyue capitalizes on cultural relics like the stone tablets of the Qing dynasty, posters of the Red Army, revolutionary texts that once stirred the masses but now lie in empty streets lined with empty houses.  \par \par \uc2 Changing times make for changing values, destruction of what was and the construction of a new vision. This is seen in demolition images made by Zhu Yan and the "ready-made" globalized urban scenes by Yu Xian.  \par \par \uc2 Modern times implies change, reformation, and transformation, and a sense of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , anxiety that what is now can be gone at any moment. The couple Shao Yinong and Mu Chen, who specialize in images of buildings of cultural importance, express that by marking all the windows of the pictured buildings with the character "Mi", a diagonal sign that recalls the paper glued on windows in war time to prevent the glass from being shattered by the tremors of bomb attacks.  \par \par \uc2 Staging photography in her gallery for contemporary art, Vanessa is the first to highlight photography as a commercial art product here. Truly an act of great courage, says Firman Ichsan, a seasoned photographer and member of the Jakarta Art Council.  \par \par \uc2 A seminar on Aug. 26 at 2 p.m. will discuss "Photography: between opinion and art", with an introduction by Oscar Motuloh, and moderated by Enin Supriyanto.  \par \par \uc2 Seduced and Abandoned An Exhibition of Contemporary Photography By Chinese Photographers Opening Aug. 25, at 7.30 p.m, on show through Sept. 25 at Vanessa Art Link, Graha MIK, Pusat Perkantoran Kuningan, Main Lobby Jl. Setiabudi Selatan kav. 16-17. Jakarta. Tel. 21 5794 1411, Info@vanessaartlink.com  \par \par \uc2 ---------------Box Photographs for Yogya Art Relief  \par \par \uc2 Coinciding with the Chinese photography exhibition, Vanessa Art Link will also display photographs for charity by Indonesian photographers, expressing similar concerns with change, destruction, culture and the perpetuation of moments in time, featuring Yogyakarta before and after the earthquake that shattered life and infrastructure in the "city of culture and art development". Participating photographers: Bambang Tri Atmojo (Atmo), Jay Subiyakto, Oscar Motuloh, Rasdian A. Vadin, Yori Antar. Proceeds of the sale will be 100 percent for the Yogyakarta Relief Project (JAR), which seeks to rehabilitate and develop the Yogja infrastructure of contemporary art. JAR is chaired by Enin Supriyanto.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060820e28k0000c\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
