\par\par \b \uc2 2007 government  \highlight22\uc2 budget \highlight\uc2 : Just more of the same?  \b0\par\par\uc2 Kahlil Rowter , Jakarta  \par \uc2 1,050 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 August 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 As the largest single entity in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the government plays an essential role, at least from a signaling standpoint. Hence the government \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  unveiled every year in August is critical. Especially now when the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is bottoming out.  \par \par \uc2 The first and most obvious piece of information we can glean from the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is the assumptions. A clarification before continuing further. Assumptions are needed to generate all other \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  numbers. But they are not government forecasts. Some are targets the government will try to achieve, and others, beyond government control, are best guesses. For example, the government will attempt to boost growth if it is below target by increasing \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . But global oil prices are certainly outside the government's hands.  \par \par \uc2 In the 2007 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , growth is assumed at 6.3 percent, the average rupiah exchange rate at 9,300 to the dollar, three-month SBI average at 8.5 percent and world oil price at US$65 per barrel. With \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  declining it is reasonable to expect growth will resume. However, a reduction in \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  will take some time to have an effect on lending rates. More immediate will be its effect of diverting more income into \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 Thus we anticipate higher consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  later this year and in early 2007. A sudden rise in government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the second half of 2006 carries inflation risks which could force the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to slow down interest rate cuts. It is therefore essential that government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  be on schedule to achieve 6.3 percent growth next year.  \par \par \uc2 Another risk is with global \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Although the U.S. Fed is looking at a decline in core inflation later this year, the jury is still out on whether this will take place and whether they can afford not to raise rates then. If they do raise rates, the space will rapidly close on how fast \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  can lower its \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rates.  \par \par \uc2 At the moment Indonesia's real interest rate differential against the US is about 0.30 percent. Should U.S. core inflation decline to 2.5 percent, and our own to 7 percent, and as long as the Fed does not increase rates, the present differential will be maintained if the \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate is reduced to 10.25 percent. If the Fed does raise rates one more time this year to 5.5 percent, the interest differential will be maintained if the BI rate is reduced only to 10.5 percent. Only when Indonesian core inflation declines to around 6 percent next year will we see BI rates in single digits.  \par \par \uc2 As regards oil prices, raising the assumption to $65 per barrel from $57 reduces the risk should actual prices remain at the present levels or rise. Our own simulation shows that if oil prices average $84 per year, the fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  here will reach Rp 100 trillion.  \par \par \uc2 Interestingly, at the same time as raising the oil price assumption to $65, which is 14 percent above the $57 assumption last year, the amount of the fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was only raised 9 percent. The electricity \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was actually cut by Rp 500 billion. The difference then is expected to be made up either by a reduction in consumption or by gasoline and kerosene substitutes like bio-fuels.  \par \par \uc2 For transportation and electricity generation this will not be easy given that large bio-fuel production capacity has yet to be built and transporting large amounts of gas to cities remains a challenge. For household cooking, the advent of the large-scale production and distribution of small gas bottles in lieu of kerosene appears promising. Especially considering kerosene absorbs a lot of the fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 A lot of disappointment has been expressed over the lowering of the 2007 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  to 0.9 percent of GDP from 1.2 percent in 2006. It should first be noted that the rise in the 2006 \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  from its formerly targeted level of 0.7 percent of GDP was due to a carryover of unspent expenditures in 2005.  \par \par \uc2 In addition, by looking at the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  from a longer-term perspective, we can arrive at a more important measure called structural \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This is calculated by dividing the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  level to trend GDP. In the case of 2007, the structural \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  rises to 2 percent of GDP from 1.9 percent in 2006.  \par \par \uc2 Another way to look at the impact of the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is by calculating the share of government consumption and capital \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  in nominal GDP. In this regard, in the 2007 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  the share is 14.3 percent compared to about 12 percent in 2006.  \par \par \uc2 From these two measures we see that the 2007 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is actually more pro-growth than previous ones. But not all of this is by design. Historically the pro-cyclical nature of Indonesian government budgets is due to 1) no built-in unemployment or social security programs; 2) growth upturns in the past have resulted in higher than anticipated fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ; 3) not all of the increase in GDP is captured by the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  system due to the large informal sector in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 As regards oil price assumptions, higher than assumed prices actually reduce the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but at the same time the fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will rise. In the past large domestic-overseas prices differences have induced smuggling and hoarding. This must not be allowed to happen again.  \par \par \uc2 Other than this we see a more realistic set of assumptions which reduce risks to the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . As regards the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , a closer inspection shows that it is actually larger than previous years. This is expected to boost \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.  \par \par \uc2 The main issue facing next year's government \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not in the design but its implementation. If the sudden burst of government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  near the end of June this year, as evidenced from second quarter GDP numbers unveiled last week, recur in a smoother manner we can expect the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to contribute to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery.  \par \par \uc2 Otherwise \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  over when actual expenditures take place and the debate surrounding them will cloud decision making and ultimately stop investors from committing.  \par \par \uc2 The writer is chief economist at CIMB-GK Securities. The views expressed here are personal.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060823e28n0000f\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
