\par\par \b \uc2 Zero ties with Israel limits Indonesia's role  \b0\par\par\uc2 Abdul Khalik , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta  \par \uc2 694 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 August 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 10\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 There should be a national debate regarding the pluses and minuses of Indonesia opening links with Israel because the lack of contact with the Jewish state is limiting Jakarta's role in the Middle East, experts say.  \par \par \uc2 The government, they assert, should soon start educating the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  on the importance of opening contacts with Israel for the country to enjoy a greater role in the Middle East, while at the same time encouraging people-to-people contact with Israelis.  \par \par \uc2 "The absence of relations has become a barrier for us to assume a mediator role in the Middle Eastern conflict. How can we become a mediator when we can't be friends with both parties involved in the conflict," political expert at the Indonesian Institute of Sciences (LIPI) Ikrar Nusa Bhakti told The Jakarta Post on Wednesday.  \par \par \uc2 He said that if President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono wished Indonesia to be a major player in bringing peace in the Middle East, his administration should start a campaign to explain to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  the benefits Indonesia and Palestine could gain if it opened contacts with the Jewish state.  \par \par \uc2 The two countries do not have diplomatic relations as Indonesia opposes Israel's repressive policies against Palestine although Indonesia agreed to a two-state solution over the Israel-Palestine conflict as stated in several UN resolutions.  \par \par \uc2 The issue of opening diplomatic relations is very sensitive, and the news of meetings between officials from the countries could have raised concerns and even lead to major protests by several Muslim groups here.  \par \par \uc2 Countries like Indonesia where the majority of the population is Muslim, like Turkey, Egypt and Jordan, however, have opened diplomatic ties with Israel.  \par \par \uc2 Although many International observers have said that Indonesia with a majority population of moderate Muslims could play a key role in bridging rifts in the Middle East because of its affinity with both the West, especially the U.S. and the Muslim world, the country has so far only issued rhetorical statements.  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's limited role in the Middle East was demonstrated by the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over whether Indonesia could join the UN peacekeeping force after Israel rejected Indonesia's participation because of the absence of diplomatic ties.  \par \par \uc2 While agreeing that the government has not raised \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  awareness on Israel and the Middle East conflict, Broto Wardoyo, an expert on Middle Eastern affairs at the University of Indonesia, said that the government should also encourage contacts between people from both countries in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 , social and cultural sectors.  \par \par \uc2 "We are not talking about opening diplomatic relations here because at this stage, resistance is still very high. What we need is more frequent visits of people from both countries so that they can see for themselves the reality. Currently, visits to Israel are only conducted by people who want to visit pilgrimage places," he told the Post .  \par \par \uc2 Broto acknowledged that people-to-people contacts needed time but stressed the result could be genuine contacts. He said that the contacts would be useful as ultimately Indonesia would open diplomatic relations with Israel once the conflict was settled, citing the 1945 Constitution as the basis for Indonesia to recognize the right of every country for independence.  \par \par \uc2 "The Indonesian people would learn that only a minority of Israelis support Zionism while most of them want to live in peace. We, at the University of Indonesia, for instance, will try to invite scholars from Israel to give lectures, to explain the mind-set of most Israelis," he said.  \par \par \uc2 Broto, however, realized that any \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  debate regarding Israel-Indonesia relations would be used as a tool by certain groups for political gain.  \par \par \uc2 Asked about the possibility of forging ties with Israel, Foreign Ministry director general for Asia, the Pacific and Africa Primo Alui Joelianto said that it was impossible for the time being to even consider forging ties, given the psyche of Indonesian domestic politics.  \par \par \uc2 "No, it is not possible. We don't want to risk conflicts here because of it. You see, we have rejected their invitation to meet, let alone any initiatives for ties," Primo told the Post .  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060825e28p0000u\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
