\par\par \b \uc2 City considers revolving fund for CNG users  \b0\par\par\uc2 Adianto P. Simamora , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta  \par \uc2 652 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 September 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 The government is considering providing a revolving fund to \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  transportation operators as an incentive to encourage the use of compressed natural gas (CNG).  \par \par \uc2 Two earlier suggestions to increase the use of CNG in Jakarta, free conversion kits or a 25 percent discount on the price, were rejected last month by the Coordinating Ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 "We are still formulating the scheme for the revolving fund," said Anton Tampubolon, city transportation scheme director at the Transportation Ministry, on Thursday.  \par \par \uc2 The Coordinating Ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has agreed to disburse Rp 40 billion to support the Blue Sky Program, which is aimed at cleaning the city's air.  \par \par \uc2 The money will be used to buy at least 4,000 converter kits for \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  buses.  \par \par \uc2 A source from the Transportation Ministry said the government was considering appointing an unnamed bank to manage the money and distribute it to \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  transportation operators. He said the operators would have to meet financial feasibility criteria, to be set by the Jakarta administration.  \par \par \uc2 The revolving fund will provide loans for operators to purchase conversion kits from three suppliers appointed by the Transportation Ministry. After a certain period of time, the operators will pay the money back to the ministry, which will return it to the fund for the use of other operators. It is not clear whether interest will charged on the loans.  \par \par \uc2 The kits, which cost between Rp 8 million and Rp 10 million, depending on the size of the vehicle's engine, are necessary to make the switch to CNG.  \par \par \uc2 The use of alternative fuels such as CNG has become a nationwide issue as the price of oil-based fuel continues to rise.  \par \par \uc2 Jakarta, the only city in the country to have a bylaw on air pollution control that requires \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  transportation to use CNG, is being used as a pilot project for the rest of Indonesia.  \par \par \uc2 The government originally promised to provide conversion kits to encourage \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  transportation operators to switch to CNG. With supplies of CNG to the city \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 , however, the administration delayed issuing a decree supporting the government on the use of CNG.  \par \par \uc2 The non-governmental organization Clean Emission Partner (MEB) says that the absence of incentives, combined with the supply problems, is discouraging bus operators from using CNG.  \par \par \uc2 "The government has to present an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  scheme to accelerate the implementation of CNG. Incentives must be given to transportation operators, businessmen, and passengers," MEB secretary general John Livingstone Wuisan told The Jakarta Post on the sidelines of a workshop on the implementation of the 2005 Air Pollution Control Bylaw.  \par \par \uc2 The Thursday workshop was aimed at formulating financial plans to support air pollution control that could be presented to the central government and the Jakarta administration.  \par \par \uc2 Among the suggestions made at the workshop, which was attended by government officials and environmental activists, were dropping the import \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  paid on conversion kits, or providing a 10 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  or soft loan for their purchase, and keeping the price of CNG at or below Rp 2,562 per liter for the next two years.  \par \par \uc2 It was also suggested that companies intending to sell CNG could be exempt from paying \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on equipment and be given an electrical \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 Participants in the seminar also said the government needed to lower fares for CNG-fueled \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  transportation and subsidize operational costs.  \par \par \uc2 John said drivers would benefit from the difference in fuel prices.  \par \par \uc2 The price of premium petrol is now around Rp 4,500 per liter.  \par \par \uc2 "However, the important thing is the sustainable supply of CNG and (regular) presence of gas stations," he said.  \par \par \uc2 Currently, only eight of the city's 264 gas stations sell CNG.  \par \par \uc2 The state-owned oil and gas company Pertamina has said it plans to convert seven of its gas stations in the city to sell CNG this year.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060901e29100009\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 AEI Objects to Nationalization Concept   \b0\par\par\uc2 238 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 September 2006\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: The Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Companies Association (AEI) objects to the concept of nationalization included in the Capital Investment Bill currently under deliberation by the House.   \par \par \uc2 Chairperson of AEI Airlangga Hartarto revealed that the nationalization in the Bill was a concept inconsistent with the government's function as a regulator under the framework of good corporate governance.   \par \par \uc2 "The article on nationalization will create \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and be inconsistent with the principle of equal treatment to all countries," he expressed his view to the House Commission VI.   \par \par \uc2 According to him, the insertion of the article on nationalization into the Bill could undermine the confidences of foreign investors in legal certainty in Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 The government, he continued, needed to provide security, in terms of physical security and business sustainability, against nationalization.   \par \par \uc2 To provide comfort to investors, he added, AEI felt that the number of institutions authorized in the investment sector should be made clear. In addition, the government was urged to design a clear system and procedures and to establish the clear authorities of the central government and the local ones.   \par \par \uc2 "According to our opinion, the Bill should define what it means by the central government, the local government, and their respective authorities," he argued.   \par \par \uc2 AEI made its argument based on the survey of investment problems conducted by the People's \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Research Institution University of Indonesia (LPEM-UI) in 2005.   \par \par \uc2 By Arif Gunawan S.   \par \par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020060904e29200005\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
