\par\par \b \uc2 Betting against the housing market in the U.S.  \b0\par\par\uc2 Paul Donovan , London  \par \uc2 958 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 September 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 The month of August was a time for reflection in financial markets. Volumes decline, as investors in the U.S. and Europe took summer vacations. Those left behind have the leisure to reflect on longer term trends and risks in the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This year, the collective focus of the international investment community has been on housing -- specifically the U.S. housing market -- and what that sector may mean for the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 U.S. housing has exerted several positive influences on the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 : Employment; direct consumption; refinancing; wealth effects. Housing allowed consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  to remain strong, even in periods when household income growth has moderated. This in turn has made sure that the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has not had a consumer led recession since 1991 (an unusually long period).  \par \par \uc2 The problem is that house prices, and housing activity, have moderated significantly this summer. In fact, UBS would go as far as to say that the housing sector of the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is in a recession. Existing home prices were rising over 10 percent a year for most of 2005 -- now they are barely moving.  \par \par \uc2 The U.S. housing sector employs a lot of people. In 2005, U.S. housing added an average of 34,000 jobs every month. In June and July of 2006, housing subtracted 15,000 jobs from the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Fewer people employed means less money to spend. Other forms of consumption are tied to the housing market as well: as people move home they tend to buy new furniture and furnishings (much of it imported from Asia).  \par \par \uc2 Mortgage refinancing -- home equity extraction -- is what really worries investors. Consumers have been borrowing more money as house prices have risen (allowing them to increase the size of their mortgages in proportion). This has allowed the U.S. consumer to spend almost without regard to their income (it helps account for the famous "negative" U.S. savings rate).  \par \par \uc2 In the first quarter of this year, home equity extraction was equal to 7 percent of disposable income in the United States. Between 2003 and 2005 it averaged 6 percent of disposable income. That makes for a lot of potential consumption.  \par \par \uc2 Of course, house prices are not (yet) falling in the U.S., and many owners have positive equity in their homes which they can still tap into. However, higher U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and slower increases in U.S. property values argue for a far slower pace of home equity extraction, and that in turn curtails the consumers' trips to the shopping mall.  \par \par \uc2 The final consideration for the U.S. housing market is the wealth effect -- and here economics ventures into more \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  territory. The wealth effect is classified under what economists call "animal spirits". Effectively consumers feel reassured about the rise in their house prices, and the increase in wealth that entails makes them feel complacent about their level of savings.  \par \par \uc2 Problems arise if consumers extrapolate from the immediate past (as human nature is inclined to do). If a consumer believes that house prices will continue to gain at 10-15 percent a year, a house price increase of only 0-5 percent will be a disappointment and cause the consumer to increase their savings rate.  \par \par \uc2 Higher savings mean consumers have to cut back on their pace of consumption, and thus act to slow \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Worse still, if house prices actually fall in the United States, the psychological damage for the consumer would be compounded. House prices have not fallen nationally in over sixty years.  \par \par \uc2 What does this mean for the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ? The world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has depended on the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to drive growth. The U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has depended on the U.S. consumer to drive growth. The U.S. consumer has depended, at least in part, on the strength of the housing market to drive growth. The chain reaction from a slowing housing sector suggests a drag on global growth.  \par \par \uc2 UBS believe that the housing slowdown in the U.S. will have a noticeable effect in slowing U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. This will, in turn, prompt the Federal Reserve to cut \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  (probably by a full 1 percent over the course of 2007), in an attempt to mitigate the growth slowdown. The Fed is unlikely to be able to stop some degree of slowdown from taking place, however, and we would expect the U.S. to slow to around 2.2 percent growth next year -- over 1 percent below where most economists would put trend.  \par \par \uc2 The problem for the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is that there is no obvious candidate to replace the U.S. consumer as an engine of growth. The external demand, or exports, that have proved a powerful support for growth in the Asian region start to fade. The growth does not disappear, but it does moderate.  \par \par \uc2 After a modest acceleration of Asian exports in the second quarter of this year, there have been some early warning signs across the region in July and August. Export numbers have come in a little weaker. Japanese industrial production data disappointed as the export sectors produced less than expected. Indonesia has some sources of domestic demand to help offset these negative global trends, but we expect Indonesian export growth to slow to below 4 percent in 2007.  \par \par \uc2 The process of globalization is something most economists endorse -- but it brings with it global consequences. The price of a two bedroom condominium in Des Moines, Iowa now has the ability to affect the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook from Jakarta.  \par \par \uc2 The writer is Deputy Head of Global Economics, UBS Investment Bank. He can be reached at paul.donovan@ubs.com.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060911e29b0000l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
