\par\par \b \uc2 Taking aggression out of management   \b0\par\par\uc2 Duncan Graham , The Jakarta Post, Surabaya   \par \uc2 911 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 September 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Two years ago Mario Sugianto was sent by his company PT ABB Sakti Industri to a training course in Bangkok.   \par \par \uc2 Assessments of his skills were mostly excellent, with a near perfect score in mathematics. And a 10 ranking for management style.   \par \par \uc2 Unfortunately he was also doing a very good job of showing measured aggression, which, while it might suit the army, is no longer appropriate in modern multinationals.   \par \par \uc2 "I was shocked," he said. "I'd gotten my MBA through the University of Western Australia and thought I was pretty good. But this was a wake up call and I had to change.   \par \par \uc2 "I was warned by psychologists on the course that this would not be easy. It wasn't -- but I've altered my behavior. I'm no longer rough and tough. I now spend more time listening. And I think it's been effective."   \par \par \uc2 Sugianto's new approach was soon tested when last December he was appointed as ABB's branch manager in Surabaya.   \par \par \uc2 The office had been without a manager for almost three years and the 66 staff and subcontractors had become slack. A workplace culture had developed which put worker interests ahead of the company.   \par \par \uc2 Cleaning up the show was never going to be easy, particularly when the new broom was young, 34, and from Jakarta.   \par \par \uc2 If Sugianto had stuck to his pre-Bangkok axe-man style he would probably have read the riot act and sacked anyone who answered back. In a previous job he had done just that, kicking out half the staff and earning great applause from his bosses and undying hatred from his former colleagues.   \par \par \uc2 "At the time I didn't care," he said. "I was 27 and considered staff over 40 to be old and slow. I didn't give them a chance to show they could change and perform better.   \par \par \uc2 "I thought this was the professional way. You can justify almost anything by saying that. Now I know I was wrong."   \par \par \uc2 So in his new position in Surabaya he opted for the personal touch, trying to understand what had gone wrong and why.   \par \par \uc2 Instead of making enemies of his colleagues he sought to win them round to accepting that things were now going to be different.   \par \par \uc2 "I told them to close the book on the past and to open a new one," he said. "I stopped blaming them for what had happened. They were good people and I needed them."   \par \par \uc2 Eventually only one person had to be shown the door.   \par \par \uc2 The Zurich-based ABB Group operates in 100 countries with a workforce of more than 107,000. It's listed on stock exchanges in its hometowns, New York and Stockholm.   \par \par \uc2 ABB makes, sells and services equipment used in electrical power generation and transmission, and turbochargers for ships and big diesel engines. Its clients are power generation authorities, factories, miners and other major users of electricity.   \par \par \uc2 In the second quarter of 2006 the company announced a big jump worldwide in orders and profit. Its main rival is Siemens.   \par \par \uc2 Earnings before the payment of interest and \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  was US$640 million compared to US$371 million in the same period last year. Most of this growth was in Europe.   \par \par \uc2 Sugianto spent the first six months of this year reorganizing the ABB office and two workshops in Surabaya, including making them flood-proof. He introduced new procedures with an emphasis on safety -- a major issue for multinationals.   \par \par \uc2 Among the other changes was the demolition of a wall separating the electrical and turbocharger workshops. The two functioned separately and would not share ideas. The turbo blokes reckoned they were the elite.   \par \par \uc2 "It was our Berlin Wall," said Sugianto. "The message was that we were all working together for one company. My style is to walk around and talk to the staff, to discuss their problems in a practical way."   \par \par \uc2 Now he is planning to open another branch in the oil city of Balikpapan, East Kalimantan, and is exploring other opportunities in Nusa Tenggara.   \par \par \uc2 "In a gloomy \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  climate with \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in law and regulations we're probably among the few optimists -- if not crazy -- who believe in this country's potential," he said.   \par \par \uc2 "Indonesians planning to work for multinationals must have an excellent command of English. Europeans are fluent in its use and the language that's used to communicate between branches around the world.   \par \par \uc2 "I was lucky that my parents pushed me to learn and stressed the importance of education. The other factors are independence, maturity and responsibility.   \par \par \uc2 "That means you can take constructive criticism, always seek to improve your performance and be responsible for everything you do. If you work well only when you're watched then you're not responsible.   \par \par \uc2 "I've learned that it's possible to turn a bad situation into something positive. Sure, it's easier to clear the workshop or office of non-performing staff and start again, but that's no challenge.   \par \par \uc2 "In the past I didn't care about people or how long they worked. I just wanted the job done. Now I think: `How would I respond if my bosses treated me like that? Workers aren't units -- they're human beings.   \par \par \uc2 "Respect others and they'll respect you. Put yourself in their shoes. Who's happy with a dictator? Who wants to work in a prison? Tyranny is not the modern style of management."   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPO