\par\par \b \uc2 Govt urged to 'get on' with infrastructure projects   \b0\par\par\uc2 Andi Haswidi , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 495 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 September 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Businesspeople at a forum hosted by Minister of Industry Fahmi Idris urged the government Tuesday to fast-track infrastructure development projects in the country to help lower the nation's high-cost \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 "We demand the government deliver its promise to build new infrastructure facilities. The poor condition of the country's infrastructure has created a high-cost \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which in turn devastates our competitiveness," Indonesian Manufacturers Association chairman Sofyan Wanandi said.   \par \par \uc2 "Instead of just making promises, its better to 'walk-the-talk' and get on with it," Sofyan said.   \par \par \uc2 Concerns about the country's lack of competitiveness have been highlighted in this year's survey by the International Institute for Management Development (IMD). Its World Competitiveness Yearbook ranks Indonesia at 60th place from 61 countries surveyed, dropping one ranking from last year's 59th place.   \par \par \uc2 The institute is an independent not-for-profit foundation located in Lausanne, Switzerland.   \par \par \uc2 "The government should not disregard surveys made by international bodies as investors will refer to them before making any investments (here)," Sofyan said.   \par \par \uc2 He said the nation's faltering infrastructure, including road and rail networks and electricity plants, had increased logistics costs, which in turn led to higher priced, less-competitive products than those made in other developing countries.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's neighbor Malaysia ranks 23rd in the survey, Thailand is at 32nd places and the Philippines ranks 49th.   \par \par \uc2 During the discussion, Minister Fahmi acknowledged the performance of industry in Indonesia had been weak. He said the government had been doing its utmost to realize the needed projects.   \par \par \uc2 Vice President Jusuf Kalla is offering Rp 500 trillion (US$54.9 billion) worth of road, rail and electricity projects to local and international investors during the next four years.   \par \par \uc2 In 2005, President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyano issued a decree supposed to give incentives to investors in the forms of \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , insurance guarantees and \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  discounts in important projects.   \par \par \uc2 However, the implementation of the decree has been hampered by \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in its investment guarantee mechanism, conflicts with existing regulations that have yet to meet international best practices, and problems in local banks' liquidity.   \par \par \uc2 The government is hoping to attract more investors at the Indonesia Infrastructure summit it is holding in November.   \par \par \uc2 Hermanto Siregar of the Brighten Institute said better, more extensive road and rail networks were key if the country's competitiveness was to improve.   \par \par \uc2 "The growth of transportation infrastructure is still too low to meet the country's (population) expansion and its demography. The total length of roads grew by only 7.14 percent from 2000 to 2004," Hermanto said.   \par \par \uc2 The condition of the nation's existing roads is also something that needs attention. The government's January report says that only 27,000 of the total 34,500 km, or 78 percent of roads, are in "excellent" condition.   \par \par \uc2 Hermanto said the mushrooming of local government levies after regional autonomy had also increased business costs.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020060920e29k00015\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\