\par\par \b \uc2 Undemocratic regions hamper growth: Analyst   \b0\par\par\uc2 Benget Simbolon Tnb. , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 432 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 October 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Despite fairly free elections at a regional level, democracy in Indonesia is still at the procedural stage, promoting the "practices of a shadow state and informal \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 " which could discourage foreign investors, a researcher says.   \par \par \uc2 Syarif Hidayat, a researcher at the Indonesia Institute of Sciences (LIPI) said here over the weekend that procedural democracy -- as opposed to substantive democracy, which is indicated by the existence of democratic behavior -- would only play into the hands of political and business elites in the country's regencies.   \par \par \uc2 "That's why almost every (election) was dominated by the local elites," he told The Jakarta Post .   \par \par \uc2 He said that this led to the practice of a "shadow state" in which the bureaucracy was powerless to deal with the local elites who forced the political process for their own benefit.   \par \par \uc2 It also caused what he termed an "informal \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ", in which elites force government officials to manipulate \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies and distort the market mechanism in regencies. He said the undemocratic behavior would generate bribery and corruption, which would in turn prolong the existence of the high-cost \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  inherited from the New Order era.   \par \par \uc2 The absence of democratic behavior might also lead to regencies pursuing unproductive projects that did not bring any \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  benefit to residents, he said.   \par \par \uc2 "How can we manage to attract foreign investors with an absence of legal certainty and market mechanisms?" he said.   \par \par \uc2 Syarif said his views were based on the results of a survey he recently conducted in several provinces, including Jambi, South Kalimantan and Bengkulu, which have seen the establishment of democratic institutions and have governors and regents directly elected by the people.   \par \par \uc2 The government revised the 1999 Regional Autonomy Law in 2004 with an additional \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  governing the direct elections of regents and governors.   \par \par \uc2 But Syarif believes that the 2004 \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  only produced a procedural democracy. The central government needs to make sure that legal enforcement of the law is strictly conducted in the regions as part of the creation of conditions suitable for foreign investors, he says.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia badly needs foreign investors to stimulate its \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which has grown by an average of only five percent a year since 1997's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis.   \par \par \uc2 The government is currently designing a comprehensive investment law that is expected to draw foreign investment, but analysts have expressed doubt over its success.   \par \par \uc2 Analysts believe that the undemocratic behavior that can lead to legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  at a regional level in Indonesia is a factor that could hamper the government's efforts to encourage investment.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020061016e2ag00006\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
