\par\par \b \uc2 The  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\uc2  rebounds, but many bumps lie ahead  \b0\par\par\uc2 Winarno Zain , Jakarta  \par \uc2 1,200 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 October 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono was only a few months in office when his administration suddenly faced severe \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  turbulence.  \par \par \uc2 Oil prices jumped to unprecedented levels, with the price in August 2005 reaching three times the price level in 2000. The burden of fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  posed the risk of dragging Indonesia to the brink of insolvency.  \par \par \uc2 At the same time, the U.S. Federal Reserve Bank was pushing up \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  with such vigor that it threatened world \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability and growth. Higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the U.S threatened capital inflows to Indonesia, and thus the stability of the rupiah.  \par \par \uc2 To save the country from impending \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  disaster, President Yudhoyono did not have many choices. Whatever decisions he took, they would involve painful \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political consequences. The day of reckoning arrived in October 2005 when the new and inexperienced administration -- after some hesitation -- decided to increase fuel prices by more than 100 percent.  \par \par \uc2 To put the brakes on spiraling inflation, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 ), had to jack up \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  from 9 to 13 percent between August and December 2005. The ensuing loss of purchasing power and more expensive borrowing costs dramatically slowed down \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth from 5.6 percent in September 2005 to 4.7 percent in March 2006. Annual growth in bank lending fell from 30 percent before the fuel-price increases to only 11 percent in July of this year. Factories were closed and millions of workers were thrown out of jobs.  \par \par \uc2 However, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  is now able to relax its monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Its key interest rate has now fallen by 300 basis points from its peak in October last year. The rupiah exchange rate, which was as low as Rp 10,300 against the U.S. dollar last year, has now strengthened to Rp 9,200 and appears to have stabilized at around this level.  \par \par \uc2 The reduction in fuel-\b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  has greatly improved the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  balance, and the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  can now be kept at a manageable level. But the government has yet to resolve the bureaucratic snags holding up government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  as civil servants adjust to the new State Finances Law.  \par \par \uc2 The government has succeeded in easing its debt service burden by exercising tighter debt management. Overall debt has come down from 55 percent of GDP at the end of 2004 to 47 percent of GDP at the present time.  \par \par \uc2 Fueled by increases in commodity prices, exports reached US$56 billion in the first seven months of this year, up 16 percent from the same period last year. Given their strong growth, it is likely that exports will reach $100 billion this year -- a new record. A slowdown in the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be unlikely to affect Indonesian exports as the slack would be taken up by increasing exports to China.  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia has been accumulating a sizable trade balance and its foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  reached an historic record of $42 billion in August of this year. When Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono was sworn in as President in October 2004, forex \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  stood at only $35 billion.  \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Stock Exchange (JSX) share price index has been breaking new records almost every week since its steep fall in May. The index has gained 85 percent since SBY took office, making it one of the best performing markets in Asia. This shows that market confidence has returned to the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , bringing in billions of dollars in capital inflows to the Indonesian capital markets.  \par \par \uc2 Even if these inflows were partly induced by favorable global and regional \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  environments, the fact remains that the fundamentals of most Indonesian publicly listed companies are still sound and promising.  \par \par \uc2 However, the performance of the Yudhoyono administration in some ways failed to live up to expectations.  \par \par \uc2 Poverty reduction efforts have still only had mixed results. The number of poor people living below the poverty line (defined by the World Bank as those earning less than $2 per day), increased by four million last year. But the causes of the increase could throw some light on what the government should do in the future. Interestingly, there are 15 million people who were previously poor who have been lifted out of poverty due to the successful cash compensation program.  \par \par \uc2 But the positive results of the program were offset by the 19 million people whose earning slipped below the poverty line, making them the "new poor". The poverty line index developed by the Central Statistics Bureau (BPS) is heavily weighted toward the price of rice, which accounts for 30 percent of the index. This means that rice prices have a significant influence over official poverty levels. The lesson from this is that if President Yudhoyono is not firm in his efforts to lower rice prices, (by importing rice if necessary), than it will be difficult to reduce poverty.  \par \par \uc2 The development of infrastructure is still too slow. Major roads and ports throughout the country are getting more and more congested, blocking the smooth movement of goods and services, causing delays and resulting in higher costs. Electricity supplies are unreliable, and frequent black-outs affect many industrial areas.  \par \par \uc2 Several big projects tendered by the government have not aroused much interest among investors. The continuing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the relevant \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  and regulations, including those issued by local governments, tends to discourage investors.  \par \par \uc2 The government has not been able to improve governance through the delivery of basic social infrastructure, such as healthcare and education services. The quality of healthcare and education has not improved -- in many cases it is even getting worse -- despite increased funding. As long as the quality of this sort of social infrastructure remains poor, it will be difficult to lift people out of poverty.  \par \par \uc2 Investment has not picked up. In the GDP component, capital formation was down by 1 percent in the second quarter of 2006 compared with same period last year. Its value for the first half of 2006 was Rp 336 trillion, or 21 percent of GDP. This was well below the 30 percent of GDP achieved in the early 1990s.  \par \par \uc2 The government's wavering attitude to the revision of the Labor Law has affected the investment climate, as the room for reducing labor costs becomes more restricted. An inflexible labor market removes the incentive for companies to hire more workers. Instead, they will use more machinery rather than workers. The failure of the government to enforce the guidelines for the setting of the local minimum wage will have an adverse effect on employment in the formal sector. As companies become hesitant to hire workers, the minimum-wage regulations will only protect those workers already employed, but close the door to millions of their colleagues who are seeking jobs.  \par \par \uc2 The Indonesian people have made a sacrifice by suffering hardship and poverty during a period of painful \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  adjustment. President Yudhoyono owes the people a payback for their sacrifice, and the only way to repay them is by working harder to achieve higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. The people deserve a better life than the one they have been experiencing for the last few years.  \par \par \uc2 The writer is an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  analyst.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020061027e2ar0000h\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Global Oil Price Declines to US$58 per Barrel  \b0\par\par\uc2 433 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 November 2006\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 Bisnis Indonesia  \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: The oil price at New York has declined to US$58.41 per barrel, following the decline on the global oil consumption.  \par \par \uc2 Bloomberg reported that heat at the US has lowered the demand on oil. In the meantime the oil reserve at the company was 12% above the average five years reserve.  \par \par \uc2 The oil price for December delivery at New York Mercantile Exchange has increased by US$0.07 to US$58.41 per barrel. On Monday, the price has declined by 3.9% or US$2.39 per barrel, the largest declined since August 17 2005.  \par \par \uc2 Analyst has predicted that during November the global oil price will be ranging from US$58 to US$62 per barrel along with eth plan of the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to cut the production by 1.2 million barrel per day.  \par \par \uc2 An analyst of Paci