\par\par \b \uc2 Govt goes all out to lure investors   \b0\par\par\uc2 Urip Hudiono , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 574 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 November 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Two key economics ministers have given assurances that Indonesia is committed to addressing the concerns of investors hoping to participate in infrastructural development in Indonesia, having instituted a number of significant reforms over the past year.   \par \par \uc2 Better project execution, smoother land acquisition, and the putting in place of risk-sharing and guarantee schemes are the government's main focuses in answering those concerns, according to Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Boediono and Finance Minister Sri Mulyani Indrawati.   \par \par \uc2 The two ministers were speaking during Wednesday's opening discussions with potential investors attending the three-day "Indonesia Infrastructure Conference and Exhibition 2006".   \par \par \uc2 It would seem that the government has learned its lesson, as it was precisely the absence of such guarantees that resulted in the failure of last year's high-profile Infrastructure Summit to attract significant interest from investors.   \par \par \uc2 In terms of improving project implementation, Boediono said the government had established a "project-development fund" to pay for detailed feasibility studies for proposed projects, and to ensure that tender documents were drawn up in compliance with international best practice.   \par \par \uc2 Boediono said that this would ensure that all the proposed projects would be ready to start immediately after the completion of the tender process, thus avoiding additional costs along the way. Assistance from the fund would be provided on a competitive basis for high-priority projects.   \par \par \uc2 Boediono also said the government had issued President \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 36/2005, as amended by \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 65/2006, on land acquisition to expedite the process and prevent the cost of project land spiraling out of control as a result of the actions of speculators.   \par \par \uc2 "We all know too well that private investors are reluctant to enter into concession agreements when significant \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  about land acquisition remain," he said.   \par \par \uc2 To overcome this, he said the government had set up a "revolving land fund" that had been provided with seed capital of Rp 600 billion (US$65 million) so far. Using this fund, the government would acquire the land needed for important projects, with the investors reimbursing it by installment as the projects began to generate revenue.   \par \par \uc2 Finance Minister Sri Mulyani Indrawati, meanwhile, highlighted the government's commitment to supporting infrastructural development through Finance Minister's \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 38/2006 on risk-sharing in infrastructure projects.   \par \par \uc2 She said the government had established an "Infrastructure Investment Fund", to which it had allocated Rp 2 trillion out of the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  in each of the years 2006 and 2007.   \par \par \uc2 This scheme basically envisages the provision of financial compensation for any political risks -- including \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  changes -- that adversely affect a project. It also envisages the extension of concession periods and the sharing of cost overruns arising from any delays in a project or lower demand for a project's output.   \par \par \uc2 However, Sri Mulyani stressed that the risk-sharing and guarantee schemes could only be availed off on a case-by-case basis based upon the legality, quality, affordability and transparency of each project in order to safeguard the interests of the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  at large.   \par \par \uc2 "We will be pragmatic and careful as we want the projects to be sustainable and really benefit the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," she said.   \par \par \uc2 "We want to give support, but we now have to do things under a new set of laws that emphasize transparency and accountability in this atmosphere of democracy. I'm sure you investors can understand this."   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020061102e2b200016\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
