\par\par \b \uc2 Can ASEAN seriously lead East Asia?  \b0\par\par\uc2 Endy M. Bayuni , Jakarta  \par \uc2 1,116 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 November 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 A retired Indonesian diplomat is skeptical that ASEAN is really in charge of any emerging East Asia regional organization even if it is the designated driver. Here is what he has to say: "I'm always in the driving seat, but it's my wife, whether seated next to me or in the back seat, who nags me where I should go, and how fast or how slow I should drive."  \par \par \uc2 That, more or less reflects the situation that the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) finds itself in today as it maneuvers to lead the wider East Asia region -- that includes \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  giants Japan, China and South Korea - toward greater \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political integration.  \par \par \uc2 The idea of an East Asia community is now being bandied about by leaders in the region, with the 10-member ASEAN taking most of the initiatives, at least for now; hence its designation as being "in the driving seat".  \par \par \uc2 But whether it can really provide the leadership, or is simply reduced to the role of a chauffeur, and for how long it can hold on to the steering wheel, remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 In the U.S., being the designated driver means, of course, that you stay sober while your drinking buddies enjoy themselves on the night out.  \par \par \uc2 The East Asia Community featured prominently at the first ASEAN Cooperation Forum in Jakarta this weekend, an event jointly organized by the host, the Centre for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS), and the Korea Foundation and Korea's Institute of Foreign Affairs and National Security.  \par \par \uc2 The next annual ASEAN summit, scheduled for the Philippine resort town of Cebu in December, will be made up of a series of summits that will also include separate meetings with the leaders of China, Japan and South Korea, and a bigger gathering known as the ASEAN Plus Three (APT). Then, there is the East Asia Summit (EAS), which includes the 13 APT countries plus India, Australia and New Zealand. In no other regional summit is the idea of building an East Asia community being formally discussed.  \par \par \uc2 Not a moment too soon, either.  \par \par \uc2 Europe is already far ahead in its integration process while North America is also forging ahead with its plan.  \par \par \uc2 The road to a community is probably a lot steeper and filled with more hurdles in East Asia than in Europe or North America.  \par \par \uc2 Asia is far larger, and (putting geography aside for now) if you include India and China in the pot, the two account already for half of the earth's population. And East Asia's population is far more heterogeneous so that forging all of the country's into a single community seems like a tall order. Then, there is the question of history.  \par \par \uc2 Difficult it may be, but it is not impossible, at least going by the statements of the leaders at the last ASEAN summits in Kuala Lumpur in December 2005, which also saw the inauguration of the East Asia Summit.  \par \par \uc2 Whether it is the 13-seater ASEAN Plus Three or the 16-seater East Asia Summit as the vehicle of choice to take the region into this community, the one thing they all seem to agree on, at least for now, is that ASEAN should be in the "driving seat."  \par \par \uc2 In most other regional organizations, usually it is the biggest member, or members, that assume the leadership position. Europe is led by Germany and France, North America is led by the United States, and even within the 10-member ASEAN, it is understood that Indonesia is the natural leader simply by the virtue of the sheer size of its population.  \par \par \uc2 Why can't either China or Japan, respectively the largest country and the largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , lead this emerging East Asian community then?  \par \par \uc2 Because their historical enmity is so deep-seated that it is unthinkable for either of them to accept the role of leader over the other. It goes much deeper than the enmity that existed between Germany and France, which seem to have managed to overcome it so as to lead the European Union together.  \par \par \uc2 Similar historical adversarial relations exist in Korea, although not so much against China as against Japan. So, Korea is also unacceptable to the other two.  \par \par \uc2 The only reason the leaders of these three North Asian countries are willing to sit together in an ASEAN-led forum is because they have reached a consensus that ASEAN should be in the driving seat.  \par \par \uc2 But being in the driving seat could mean anything but leading the group.  \par \par \uc2 Can ASEAN resist the backroom pressures from both China and Japan as each try to influence the direction and pace of regional integration?  \par \par \uc2 Rivalry between them on community-building is reflected by the creation of two separate vehicles, the APT and EAS, to take the region in the direction of the envisaged community.  \par \par \uc2 China's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  may still be half the size of Japan's, but it is growing rapidly that so that some years down the road Japan will lose the only edge it has over China today.  \par \par \uc2 The EAS, in some sense, is aimed at neutralizing China's perceived domination by bringing India into the picture along with Australia and New Zealand. Concerns over Chinese domination are also shared by some ASEAN members with the result that they endorsed the redefinition of geography involved in the creation of the EAS.  \par \par \uc2 There is also the question of the role of the United States in the emerging community. Again in defiance of geography, some countries in this part of the world feel the need of some sort of U.S. presence in the regional structure, if not for security and political reasons, then on account of the fact that the economies of Asia are very much tied to America's.  \par \par \uc2 It is unclear, however, how long China would be content to allow this emerging community to be wagged by the tail before deciding to take over the steering wheel from ASEAN's hands. What is sure is that the countries in the region, while forging ahead with the idea of a community and accepting China's rising power, are hedging against a possible change of \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Beijing.  \par \par \uc2 For now, both avenues are being explored as a means for building the envisaged East Asian community. In diplomatic parlance, APT is designated for functional cooperation and EAS is designed more as a forum for dialog.  \par \par \uc2 And ASEAN is content to be the designated driver, whatever this really means.  \par \par \uc2 The writer is chief editor of The Jakarta Post . He took part in the First Korea-ASEAN forum in Jakarta on Nov. 11-12.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020061114e2be0000h\par }\page {\par\fs20\b  \highlight22\uc2 Central Bank \highlight\uc2  Must Increase Interest Rate: G-20  \b0\par\par\uc2 465 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 November 2006\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 Bisnis Indonesia  \par \par \uc2 MELBOURNE: Amid the effort of Indonesia to lower the benchmark BI Rate, the decision makers of 20 world's largest economies have called for central banks to increase the interest rate to control inflationary pressures.  \par \par \uc2 "Amid the higher inflationary pressure, the normalization of monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of the members of G-20 should be maintained," the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  governors and the finance ministers of G-20 said in a statement yester