\par\par \b \uc2 Growing income disparity puts RI  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\uc2  at risk  \b0\par\par\uc2 Kahlil Rowter , Jakarta  \par \uc2 1,019 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 December 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 It does not require statistical analysis to see growing disparity in Indonesia. But this is not confined to this country alone. A number of other Asian countries have actually fallen back in their drive for equitable income distribution. Two features of Indonesia stand out, however. First, data on equality is inadequate, leading to false conclusions. Second, and as a consequence, there does not seem to be any urgency for the government to do anything to remedy the situation.  \par \par \uc2 One measure to track income equality is called the Gini Coefficient. This is calculated by plotting a curve, the axes of which are the share of the population -- from poor to rich -- against their shares of the national income. The values are between 0 and 1, where 0 means complete equality and 1 means all income accrued to any one person.  \par \par \uc2 Surprisingly, Indonesia's Gini Coefficient first worsened from 0.33 in 1987 to 0.36 in 1996, and then improved to 0.27 in 2002. One possible explanation was that the crisis that started in 1997 first hit urban fixed-income earners. Then the wave of the crisis hit the poor, but this was mitigated by the fact that agricultural producers were spared the worse effects. The poor were also helped by the existence of social safety nets -- both formal and informal.  \par \par \uc2 It is not easy to acquire statistics for 2002-2006, but given the recent rise in unemployment and poverty, it is reasonable to expect that inequality has risen. Furthermore, the tradable sectors (mostly labor-intensive) have grown by only 3.4 percent annually since 2001, while the non-tradable (mostly capital intensive) sectors grew by 6.3 percent in the same period. It is no wonder that the 5-5.6 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth we have been experiencing in the last few years is generating so few jobs, hence the rise in unemployment.  \par \par \uc2 Although the 2005-2006 increase in poverty is blamed on increasing rice prices, the growth pattern favoring capital-intensive sectors remains the underlying cause. The fact is, Indonesia is not growing enough to create enough jobs. But even if growth alone rises to pre-crisis levels, the underlying pattern would still cause rising unemployment.  \par \par \uc2 So how do we reconcile higher unemployment and rising poverty with improvement in income equality? Both cannot be right.  \par \par \uc2 I contend that the equality statistics are flawed. The first problem is that practically no income statistics exist in Indonesia. The labor survey does not record income above a meager level. And the usual data used to measure inequality is based on \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 , not income.  \par \par \uc2 Certainly in the lower-income groups, \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  and income are about equal. But not for the higher-income groups. For them, \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  is much lower than income, the difference being saved. Hence calculations based on \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  naturally understate income disparity. Using \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  data alone we cannot hope to capture the income of those with bank deposits in the billions.  \par \par \uc2 Another anomaly found only in Indonesia is higher wage growth for unskilled worker. While in other countries the more natural pattern is for skilled worker wages to grow faster. One possible explanation for the Indonesian case is that the rapid minimum wage increase in recent year has left the skilled worker wage level behind. This might be true for firms employing a lot of minimum wage workers, but almost impossible where unskilled laborers work alongside their more skilled colleagues.  \par \par \uc2 Aside from the obvious country-specific reasons what fundamental factors caused this Asian phenomenon? A recent International Monetary Fund study ( Asian Regional Outlook , September 2006) argued that inequality first rises and then slowly reverses in direction once income rises above a certain threshold. For Indonesia, this is about 30 percent from the present level.  \par \par \uc2 Contrary to long-standing advice from international organizations, trade openness does not seem to significantly help income equality. Skilled workers appear to get the early benefits of export-led production expansion.  \par \par \uc2 I believe this is also what has occurred here. The rise in the finance and banking, telecom and automotive sectors -- which explains a lot of growth recently -- has disproportionately benefited skilled workers in these sectors.  \par \par \uc2 Unlike Indonesia, other countries are taking notice. In Japan, disparity was the main rallying point in this year's election for prime minister. The Korean president made income disparity a key point in his New Year's speech. India has started an income equalization program. Even Malaysia has made combating the income gap its highest priority in its latest \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  plan.  \par \par \uc2 How will they go about it? Malaysia aims to eradicate poverty by 2010. Next is to reduce rural-urban poverty by providing sustainable income-generating activities. At the same time, housing, education, health services, utilities and transportation will be provided. These are similar to Indonesia.  \par \par \uc2 What we do not see here are specific targets, like having the 40 percent lowest-income population earning at least 20 percent of the national income and a Gini Coefficient at, say, 0.35, sometime in the future.  \par \par \uc2 Of course, a sustainable high \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is a pre-requisite to any disparity alleviation program. But a focus on education is also needed. Other policies that promise to help include improving access to the financial market. This is the thrust of the program advocated by De Soto. It is expected that better access to the financial market would help the informal sector and improve growth distribution, now confined to a few narrow activities.  \par \par \uc2 In short, Indonesia's disparity is growing despite statistical evidence to the contrary. These statistics need improvement. Without awareness of the problem there is no political urgency, despite the evidence that something very basic and very wrong is taking place. This is our main problem. Quick realization is essential. Next come pertinent policies.  \par \par \uc2 Without them, the problem will get worse, leading to low productivity and even breakdowns, requiring more expensive remedies later. Heightened social divisions also increase \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and divert resources from productive to re-distributive use.  \par \par \uc2 The writer is Chief Economist CIMB-GK Indonesia. This is a personal opinion.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020061207e2c70000l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
