es, and 24 projects in the transportation and motorized vehicle industries.  \par \par \uc2 "The realization of investments in the metal, machinery, and electronic industries this year has increased from US$522.9 million in 2005," Agus said during the expose of 2006 Industrial Performance Prognosis and 2007 Working Program in Jakarta on Thursday.  \par \par \uc2 However, he reminded, there were still some imminent investment barriers in 2006, such as macro-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fluctuation following the soaring international crude oil price to US$70 per barrel, high interest rate (BI Rate), lack of supporting infrastructures, political and security \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , declining purchasing power, and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  investment incentives.  \par \par \uc2 Plan for 2007  \par \par \uc2 Agus explained that the Department of Industry could not set a specific target about investment outlook in 2007.  \par \par \uc2 He stated that if the investment climate next year was still similar with that in 2006, the government would try to boost installed capacities in the leading industrial sectors, such as the machinery, agro-business, metal, and transportation sectors.  \par \par \uc2 "For example, the utilization rate of the transportation industry is still between 50%-55%. So, even without investments they still can boost their installed capacities," added Agus.  \par \par \uc2 He continued that the government hoped the realization of investments in 2007 would improve as the provision of investment incentives regulated in the Revised Governmental \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 148/200, which would be approved early next year, was expected to be able to lure foreign investors to Indonesia.  \par \par \uc2 "In addition, Indonesia has also had the Custom Law to anticipate illegal and import and to eliminate other high-cot \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 