\par\par \b \uc2 Reform must start from presidential office  \b0\par\par\uc2 Wimar Witoelar , Jakarta  \par \uc2 1,462 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 December 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Ever since 1998 made "reform" the most popular word in local politics, its meaning has become more elusive every year. This will continue in 2007. Reform is like dieting. The more you try, the more you know about it, but the more you discover how difficult it is.  \par \par \uc2 The problem is that reform, like dieting, is not just a question of will, but also of choosing the right combination of tradeoffs. Everyone knows the good things that need to be done, but the hard part is to stop doing the bad things.  \par \par \uc2 You need good guys in government but bad guys are more dedicated to the pursuit of power. When you elect a good guy to a position of leadership, the bad guys undermine his leadership with money and dirty tricks. The moderately good guy tries to appease the bad guys so he can remain in power by making everybody happy -- a mission impossible.  \par \par \uc2 All you have left is a mess from which opportunists can collect their pickings.  \par \par \uc2 Here is where the conundrum lies. Broadly defined, a conundrum is any problem where the answer is very complex. We can make things less complex if we involve people in looking for solutions but reserve the decisions for ourselves. Rather than turning the reform issue into a political football, remember what Confucius said, "Life is really simple, but we insist on making it complicated".  \par \par \uc2 When President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono says, "Reform is not as easy as turning over your palm, it takes time," the question is, does he really intend to turn over his palm? This is an important question, because the President has the largest role to play in reform. The President is more instrumental in reform than his Cabinet, than political parties and members of the legislature, than the bureaucracy or the military, and certainly more than the Vice President. The President stands alone.  \par \par \uc2 Where he points, the nation follows.  \par \par \uc2 The President might be punished if he tries too hard to reform the country, but the nation will benefit from his initiative. Some might find Abdurrahman Wahid's political journey unsuccessful, but three areas of reform remain a legacy to the nation: ethnic and religious pluralism, a reduction in military dominance and the empowerment of civil society. Reforms stay in the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  mind even when they flounder later on. The world remembers the "Prague Spring" of 1968, when Alexander Dubcek introduced political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms. Later tanks rolled into Czechoslovakia and the nation went back into hard-line hands. But the seeds of reform had been sown, the fruits of which were harvested some twenty years later making Europe what it is today.  \par \par \uc2 Some might find the Yudhoyono presidency does not call for such dramatic events. Yudhoyono wants to reform at a moderate pace. He is a decent person but not a firebrand reformer. He made his own changes slowly over time, from a Soeharto loyalist to a democratic bureaucrat.  \par \par \uc2 His military background shows in his personal discipline and respect for seniors. Unfortunately decisiveness is not part of his character portfolio.  \par \par \uc2 The issue is, can Indonesia afford a president like the Yudhoyono of 2004-2006, \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  in purpose and action, always hesitating? Can we make the Yudhoyono of 2007 more presidential in assuming authority, providing direction, and most importantly, can Indonesia look forward to a president who is clear and active on reform? How should the President react to the constant wrangling between political elite groups that in the end curtail the reform and prevent the administration delivering promises to its constituents?  \par \par \uc2 First of all, a president should not react to politics; he should be proactive in finessing political conflict. Much has been written about Yudhoyono not having a political base and the necessity of keeping Golkar happy. Those who know Indonesia's political history and the nature of our politicians know that politicians thrive in a vacuum. When there is no national leadership, the politicians step in. But when the wind is blowing with firm political leadership, politicians follow the wind.  \par \par \uc2 The case of Jusuf Kalla is highly revealing. From a non-political background Kalla joined Golkar bringing large financial contributions. When Golkar failed to nominate him for president in 2004, he deserted the Golkar campaign to join Yudhoyono.  \par \par \uc2 As for Golkar, once their candidate Wiranto was defeated, they flocked to Kalla and made him chairman to gain executive access. When the VP was defeated in the showdown over the UKP3R (the unwieldy acronym for the three-person team assigned to speed up government reform), Golkar officials started to challenge Kalla's chairmanship.  \par \par \uc2 Like President Bush, Kalla is a lame duck and Golkar might support Yudhoyono directly if he showed the backbone to accommodate that support.  \par \par \uc2 Otherwise, Yudhoyono could go straight to the people by remaking his Democrat Party.  \par \par \uc2 Optimism has to rest on hope, and our hope certainly is that he will emerge as the reformist president as he is often portrayed in his campaign image. The brouhaha over the appointment of UKP3R proves that deep inside the hesitant President lies the heart of a decent person.  \par \par \uc2 Now comes the entree after this appetizer of ideas. You do not have to change the president's personality to make him a good president. You just need to improve his support system. Yudhoyono is Indonesia's first directly elected president, and holds the world record for gathering the highest number of direct votes (67,196,112) and highest percentage (60.9 percent) in a presidential election. In comparison, George W, Bush won his presidency in 2000 by 50,460,110 votes which were in fact less than his opponent Al Gore's tally of 51,003,926. Bush was declared the winner because the U.S. does not vote for its president by direct vote, but through the Electoral College. Yet Yudhoyono does not show signs of having the world's strongest mandate. When Bush came to Bogor, Yudhoyono looked much less confident than the U.S. President who had been repudiated by his constituency.  \par \par \uc2 Since Yudhoyono appointed his first Cabinet, he has not been in control of the decision on personnel appointments, yielding to Vice President Kalla who was elevated to national figure status by his association with the winning candidate. This has led to a somewhat disjointed support system. Reform of the President's office must eliminate this dualistic conflict of interest.  \par \par \uc2 The President's office does not articulate its political agenda in other than normative terms. The President has able spokespersons who speak in the style of the eighties, rich in bureaucratic content. The presidential secretariat and the Cabinet secretariat have disappeared. In previous administrations they have helped to streamline the coordination of presidential tasks. The State Secretariat has no special function related to the presidency. It stands as an unwieldy reminder of Soeharto-style bureaucracy, obstructing rather than assisting reform. This is especially true in dealing with foreign governments and NGOs where they undermine the efforts of Yudhoyono in portraying a modern international image.  \par \par \uc2 You could go on from these findings to recommend structural change in the office of the president. But administrative tinkering will not transform Yudhoyono into the type of president the nation needs. You need to reduce the baggage that hinders him from becoming a strong leader. First, we need a vice president who strengthens the popularity and authority of the president, not weakens it. The President's slow tempo should not be an excuse for the Vice President to preempt him. The Vice President should act in the President's interests, preparing his brief and assisting in follow-up. Most importantly, as Kalla shows a penchant for \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  speaking, he should be the President's main spokesperson, as the official spokespersons seem unable to rally \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  opinion behind the President's reform agenda.  \par \par \uc2 With the recent launching of the UKP3R, the lack of a reform agenda may be swiftly overcome. Reform does not require reinvention. It just calls for a reactivation of the directions Indonesia has shown to the world: Human rights protection, anticorruption measures, and legal reform. All others follow these basic reforms. They were the theme of Yudhoyono's campaign, set aside to placate pressure groups who have jumped on his bandwagon.  \par \par \uc2 Bureaucratic reform of the presidential office should be designed to enable a sharp focus on the reformist theme.  \par \par \uc2 The year 2007 may give us a new reformist President, still the same Yudhoyono but strengthened by a support system which can bring out the best in him. Keep things simple, go for the jugular. The \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  will support the President whom they voted into power in 2004.  \par \par \uc2 The writer is a political analyst. He can be reached at wimar@perspektif.net  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020061229e2ct00013\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
