\par\par \b \uc2 Restoring Indonesia's  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\uc2  to a higher growth path  \b0\par\par\uc2 Christopher Lingle , Ubud, Bali  \par \uc2 1,523 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 December 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Over the 25 years up to 1996, Indonesia experienced average annual \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 7 percent while poverty declined from 40 percent of the population in 1976 to 11 percent. But this stellar performance came to a rude end during the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and financial turmoil that swept across East Asia beginning in 1997.  \par \par \uc2 Since then, attempts to restore Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to a sustainable path of high growth have met with limited success. As it is, annual GDP growth since 1997 averaged only 2.6 percent if 1998 is included when the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  shrank by 13 percent. Only recently has per capita income reached its pre-1996 peak.  \par \par \uc2 Jakarta has taken steps that should be applauded, For example, sales of publicly-owned assets, reduced \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  deficits and less government control of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  helped push the ratio of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 -sector debt to GDP down from a high of 94 percent in 2000 to 39 percent this year. Consequently, debt servicing payments fell from 24 percent of the total \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2000 to 11 percent of total government \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 All these steps have helped reduce sovereign risk. As such, credit-rating agencies raised credit-rating risk on government debt with Indonesian sovereign debt now rated by Moody's as B1 and by Standard & Poor's as B+.  \par \par \uc2 But improvements on the macroeconomic side have not been matched by gains on the microeconomic side. For example, unemployment has risen every year for the past 10, increasing from 5 percent to 11 percent of the labor force and underemployment is estimated to be 40 percent of the workforce.  \par \par \uc2 Initially, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  rebound was hindered by the heavy costs of recapitalizing a collapsed banking system that were the most expensive in the world, costing 15 percent of GDP. But the biggest problem is that investment never staged a full recovery. From the late 1980s to 1997, Indonesia attracted more than US$23 billion in FDI. But since 1997, there has been a net outflow of $8.0 billion.  \par \par \uc2 If there is any hope for a return to the glory days, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the central government must abandon conventional macroeconomic dogma. In particular, \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  choices based on the mistaken beliefs that household consumption, government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  or exports are drivers of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, should be jettisoned.  \par \par \uc2 These misguided macroeconomic myths induce the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to tamper with \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  to create an artificial and temporary boost in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity. A similar intent drives higher \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , often based upon new \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 -sector debt. But by themselves, neither more consumption nor higher \b \highlight22\uc2 public spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  will bring a sustained rise in prosperity.  \par \par \uc2 As it is, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  booms based on \b \highlight22\uc2 public spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  or artificially-low \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are illusory and temporary. Sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth requires increased real earnings and should be supported by increased productivity that comes from more and better investments.  \par \par \uc2 But the private sector will invest more only if \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals improve. Neither the amount of pieces of paper money nor the amount of government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  or its timing can change anything real about the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 For its part, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  operates under a mistaken belief that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth can be fine-tuned or manufactured by fiddling with \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . It uses the BI rate to act as a reference for bank rates and bill sales. Lower rates are expected to induce banks to lower their rates and lend more to households and businesses to boost consumption and investment as a prelude to higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.  \par \par \uc2 Artificially-low \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  (or increased government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) can trick consumers or business leaders into being more confident. But when temporary stimuli dry up or are reversed, new borrowing or investment inspired by higher future expectations will be unfulfilled.  \par \par \uc2 A reversal of \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 -induced stimuli is inevitable and occurs when consumer prices begin to rise. Then, ill-advised investments must be liquidated so that unemployment rises as the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  slows down.  \par \par \uc2 In all events, lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut both ways. Lower deposit rates discourage some amount of savings. And since the stock of real savings out of long-term income is the basis of sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, less saving leads to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  underperformance.  \par \par \uc2 Unfortunately, the belief in voodoo macroeconomics does not end with monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Earlier this year, chief economics minister Boediono announced that \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 -sector \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be accelerated in order to stimulate the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . His game plan predictably failed because the timing of government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , per se, cannot boost real \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.  \par \par \uc2 Frontloading government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  cannot have a greater benefit than leaving it to a later date. But never mind timing, fantasies of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  textbooks aside, the real world provides no evidence that government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  permanently stimulates higher real \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. If prosperity and recovery could be conjured up by increasing government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , no country on earth would be poor!  \par \par \uc2 As such, monetary and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  will NOT solve Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems because they boost total demand artificially. It is far better for households and businesses to be given greater control over their earnings and \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the basis of sustainable investment so more new jobs and more wealth are created.  \par \par \uc2 A third recommendation for changing Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  orientation is to shift away from an obsession with export-led growth and recovery. While increased foreign demand for goods and services is a good thing, it is a poor substitute for having a healthy and competitive domestic sector of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 In all events, the advantages from trading are NOT from exporting. Adam Smith view discredited this notion in his withering attack on mercantilism and imperialism in the 18th Century.  \par \par \uc2 Instead, the advantages of trade are in allowing producers and consumers to buy from least-cost providers. As such, imports are a better motivator of growth since they enhance efficiency and increase real purchasing power as a basis for sustained \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.  \par \par \uc2 And greater competition induces domestic producers to be more innovative and efficient. When such improvements bring gains in labor productivity, higher wages contribute to rising household incomes and greater consumption. Productivity gains also boost profits as unit costs decline whereby enhanced shareholders wealth boosts domestic consumption.  \par \par \uc2 Then the benefits extend to the international sector since businesses can import inputs or intermediate goods that lower operating costs. Falling costs and rising productivity will then enhance the ability to export without any government \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  interventions.  \par \par \uc2 In the end, President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono faces a clear choice in the approach to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . He can make populist promises of redistribution that bring temporary \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  gains and electoral gains. Or he can provide the leadership to promote policies that lead to sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.  \par \par \uc2 These choices are incompatible. Up to now, he and his team deserve praise for pushing through some unpopular measures to help sort out government finances.  \par \par \uc2 Their job in the future can be made easier if citizens understand that attempts to promote employment through \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  involve NO net gains to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This is because salary payments to a new government employee create \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  obligations that kill off private-sector jobs since businesses have less to spend.  \par \par \uc2 The best-case \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  scenario for more government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  is a "zero-sum game" whereby gains exactly offset losses. But administrative costs and deadweight losses of government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  tend towards a "negative-sum game" whereby overall losses exceed overall gains.  \par \par \uc2 As such, net employment growth can only occur through undertaking by private sector actors. This can be facilitated by introducing more market-based \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms can reduce the barriers to business while increasing labor market flexibility.  \par \par \uc2 It would also help if government interferences and regulations are inventoried so unnecessary interventions can be eliminated. Currently, the costs of doing business in Indonesia are high and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  since both domestic and foreign investors face a bureaucratic swamp of red tape and corruption.  \par \par \uc2 Understanding that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  future can be brighter if better \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  choices are made. It shows that whether future \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance involves greater poverty or more prosperity is a matter of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 -\b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  choices. As such, pessimistic and fatalistic notions like a "poverty trap" as a natural condition can and should be discarded.  \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister Boediono, Finance Minister Sri Mulyani Indrawati and \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Governor Burhanuddin Abdullah had considerable success. For example, they oversaw \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform to reinvigorate the local investment climate and speed up dispute resolution encountered by foreign investors. And they took steps to restore \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  balance sheets so the ratio of Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 -sector debt to GDP is the lowest in ASEAN (except for Singapore with zero debt).  \par \par \uc2 They or their successors have to muster sufficient political will to do more to enhance the opportunities for job and wealth creation in the second largest democracy. A first step in this direction involves the realization that policies of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the central government are the main cause of macroeconomic instability and sluggish growth. <br>  \par \par \uc2 The writer is Senior Fellow at the Centre for Civil Society in New Delhi and Visiting Professor of Economics at Universidad Francisco Marroquin in Guatemala.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020061230e2cu00012\par }\par \b \uc2 Search Summary\b0\par \par  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx2000\clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx9072\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Text\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \li50\uc2 (economic or economy) and (uncertain or uncertainty or uncertainties) and (policy or publ